***The National Electronic Dance Music Conference***

http://www.nedmc.com

Important dates to remember:

March 6th - Seminar and Panel lists announced
March 15th - Exhibit registration begins
March 31st - Attendee registration begins
Be sure to be on the lookout for registration specials that will end =
April 30th.

  Please visit http://www.nedmc.com/seminars.html for information =
regarding our seminars and panels.

  In Washington D.C. on September 3rd through 6th 2004, the National EDM =
Conference will take place at the Omni Shoreham Hotel. We will be =
utilizing the entire space of the hotel to bring you the best possible =
environment to network with others in the EDM industry. We will be =
hosting all genres, from hip hop to hardcore, from house to industrial. =
As well, we will also be showcasing the newest technologies for the =
coming year and beyond, as well as offering seminars and focus groups to =
help dj's, producers, and gear manufacturer's push the envelope of music =
production and presentation.

  We have chosen D.C. to host this event because it is a central =
location on the east coast, offering easy access from many spots around =
the country, as well as being home to one of the nations largest EDM =
focused communities. We will be working closely with all businesses =
involved to ensure top notch production on all sides for after hours =
events, as well as demonstrations of said products. There will be also =
attendee only events, so be sure to sign up early to gain access to =
these events, held exclusively in the hotel.

  If you are interested in speaking on a panel or having your company =
host a seminar, please email randy@nedmc.com

  To stay up to date on all the happenings of the NEDMC, including =
seminar information, hotel and registration discounts, and event =
information, please visit http://www.nedmc.com/contact.html

  For further information on either sponsoring, exhibiting, attending, =
or hosting an official event, please email info@nedmc.com , or visit our =
site at http://www.nedmc.com .

  If you would like to help out with the NEDMC, please e-mail =
amanda@nedmc.com for intern and volunteering opportunites.=20


http://www.nedmc.com
The National Electronic Dance Music Conference

Fairfax, VA 22038

so, yes, I know everyone including me loves to hate on 1015; and with =
good reason. Overpriced, Security Strip-Searches, $8 drinks, and not a =
real 'cool' vibe. But, I also know y'all love to support your local =
dj's, so that is why I am here.=20

A very good friend of mine, Jeff aka 'fLOORCRAfT', has the distinct =
opportunity to rock the vip room, aka top floor, from 11 - 12 tonight. I =
would consider it a personal favor for any of you to come out and =
support. Jeff is a great dj, and works very hard at creating a positive =
scene.=20

And to be honest, the only way 'we' are going to change the mentality of =
theses big clubs is to support our local dj's, who work very hard and =
often for very little in return. So, with that said, I will see some of =
you tonight. cheers!

Subject: [sfraves] SRR: MIX ONLINE!!!

Well, after MUCH trial and tribulation, I finally got a full mix (albeit a 
very old mix) onto my site. I initially tried to upload this mix around a 
year ago, and little did I know but the file didn't upload properly, and 
only 45 minutes of a 78 minute mix survived.

I finally fixed everything and got that mix up. So, if you're into 
progressive, tech-house & breaks with a tribal flare, go catch a listen!!!

Bear in mind that A. it's an older mix with stuff I don't play as regularly 
anymore, and B. that it's not a perfect mix - there's a bad EQ issue a 
little over 1/2way thru (plus a minor wreck in there as well). I'm not one 
to sugar-coat things tho - so if you're anal about perfect mixes, you might 
noit like it. Other than those two spots everything seemed pretty spot-on.

Soon I will have a new mix, sans noticeable flaws and with the new stuff 
I've been jocking up to listen to....soon. I promise!

Here ya go:    http://www.djmarcom.com

The mix is called "TATTOO SESSIONS VOL 1"

Marc(O)
*THWAP!*//Substructure//Mario Bros.
DC/MD/VA/CA
deep.funky.techy.tribal.progressive.nuskool.beats&bass

Subject: Re: [sfraves] SRR: MIX ONLINE!!!

As an aside -

Someone I respect very much (wink wink) told me I should "never make any
excuses about my mixes".

Sorry if it came off like that. I just don't like to misrepresent my work. I
honestly don't give a fuck that there ARE any flaws on the mix, otherwise I
wouldn't have bothered mentioning it.

It's NOT a demo, I didn't plan the mix (it was something I made when I came
home from work one afternoon), and it was made with some new records I had
just gotten from eBay.

I just figured people might like something to bump in the office, or while
they got ready to go out tonight or some shit.

*shrug*

That all being said - anything going on in the East Bay tonight that's cheap
and/or free? I have no plans and am really trying to avoid the "sit at home
on Friday bored senseless" thing again this weekend...

If they are in fact heavy, and you're using 1200s, all you gotta do is adjust 
the weight on the end of the tonearm.  It doesn't matter if a cart is light or 
heavy, as long as the weight's within the 1200 tonearm's parameters.

Frank

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Troubling question.... about Shure's Whitelabel

I replied in private to the initial post before, but since ti's still a
thread...

I used the White Labels a bunch of times, and I was fairly impressed by
them. Very responsive, nice tracking, and they seem really well balanced
overall.

My only gripe is the price tag - but seeing as how even Ortofon Concordes
are around $120 per cartridge brand new, it's not all that much of a
difference (average of around $130 or so).

They get the thumbs up from me...

M-

Subject: [sfraves] Re: lazy nrr

	If you don't want Martha Stewart to go to jail for 20 years, and you 
believe in fairness and equality under the law (as opposed to special 
treatment for Ms. Stewart because you think she's a good person) then 
the conclusion is inescapable:

	You should support the elimination of laws against insider trading, or 
at least a reduction in the penalties for violating such laws, because 
a jury found her guilty of breaking them and she is simply facing the 
penalty prescribed by law that anyone else would be facing in a similar 
situation. If she shouldn't face that penalty then neither should 
anyone else.

	Please note that I'm not taking any position on insider trading (I 
actually have very mixed feelings about it). I'm just encouraging 
people not to have double standards.

Groove on,
					<<< Starchild >>>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Re: lazy nrr

Actually, she did not get convicted of insider trading. She got convicted
of conspiracy, obstruction of justice, and perjury. All these charges stem
from the investigation into the insider trading allegations, rather than
the (alleged) insider trading activity itself.


On Sat, 6 Mar 2004, Starchild wrote:

> 	If you don't want Martha Stewart to go to jail for 20 years, and you
> believe in fairness and equality under the law (as opposed to special
> treatment for Ms. Stewart because you think she's a good person) then
> the conclusion is inescapable:
>
> 	You should support the elimination of laws against insider trading, or
> at least a reduction in the penalties for violating such laws, because
> a jury found her guilty of breaking them and she is simply facing the
> penalty prescribed by law that anyone else would be facing in a similar
> situation. If she shouldn't face that penalty then neither should
> anyone else.
>
> 	Please note that I'm not taking any position on insider trading (I
> actually have very mixed feelings about it). I'm just encouraging
> people not to have double standards.
>

land CA **

INNERACTIVE NIGHT @ KINGMAN'S

Saturday, March 6th Inneractive Crew will be hosting a FREE night at the be=
autiful Kingman's Lucky Lounge in Oakland, CA. Join us for funky beats, an =
incredible vibe, great drinks and a little March madness.

It's Inneractive night with all of our resident dj^=D2s spinning house, bre=
aks and drum & bass.

djs for the evening include:

a very special guest - dj Robynn (Witches Brew, Collection, Free Flo Friday=
s) - Throwing down 2-Step and 4-to-da-floor vinyls. http://collection.whati=
tiz.biz/   http://www.mrnitesgroove.com/

Lonestar (Inneractive, Lil House on Da Sev')
UrbanTiger (Inneractive, Reality Ripple)

Kingman's is located at 3332 Grand Avenue.

This event rocks from 8pm-2am.
21+ w/ id.

Stylish dress encouraged.

info: www.inneractivecrew.com

This is part of the Anarchist Cafe, a benefit for the Anarchist Bookfair an=
d anarchist political prisoner Sherman Austin

The Bay Area Anarchist Bookfair, now in its ninth year, takes places on Sat=
urday, March 13 from 10am to 6pm at the S.F. County Fair Building on 9th Av=
enue in Golden Gate Park.  Admission is free, and speakers include Starhawk=
, Alexander Cockburn, Jeffrey St. Clair, Lynn Breedlove, Tim^=D2M T. West, =
Katya Komisaruk, Agent Apple of the Biotic Baking Brigade, Susan Greene, Su=
n Frog and Sean Sullivan.  For more information call (415) 431-8355.

Sherman Austin, a 20 year-old, black, Southern California anarchist, was th=
e webmaster of the site www.raisethefist.com. He is the first person to be =
charged under 18 U.S.C. 842(p), a 1997 "anti-terrorism" law authored by Cal=
ifornia Senator Dianne Feinstein.  What was Austin^=D2s crime?  He had had =
offered free hosting and a link on his website to a site he did not author =
called The Reclaim Guide, offering general security culture information alo=
ng with a small portion dealing with explosives.  This information is publi=
cly available, yet Austin has been jailed for merely linking to it.

On August 4, Sherman Austin was sentened to one year in federal prison and =
three years probation.  His probation includes the following terms: Austin =
cannot possess or access a computer of any kind without prior approval of h=
is probation officer; if he gets that approval, the equipment is subject to=
 monitoring and to search and seizure at any time, without notice; he must =
surrender his phone, DSL, electric, and satellite bills to his probation of=
ficer; and he cannot associate with any person or group--environmental, soc=
ial justice, political, or economic--that seeks to change the government in=
 any way.

Although Austin initially planned to fight the charge and go to trial, he a=
ccepted a plea bargain after being threatened with serving up to 20 years i=
n jail. Despite both the FBI and the Justice Department agreeing on a sente=
nce of four months in jail and four months in community confinement, the ju=
dge increased the sentence to set an example for future "revolutionaries."


For more information about Sherman Austin, please see:

www.freesherman.org
http://www.counterpunch.org/merlin08162003.html
http://rwor.org/a/1217/austin.htm
http://www.infoshop.org/shermanaustin.html

a
web site for electronic music lovers around the world.  I've done pretty
good so far, with over 900 members on the site.  The site has a whole =
bunch
of goodies, but I don't want to bore anyone with that.  You all can =
check
out for yourself at www.djunderground.com =
<http://www.djunderground.com/> .

=20

Well, I've been thinking lately that I want to expand the site and offer
reviews of my experiences at clubs and venues I visit in the bay area on =
the
weekend.  I've realized that there is no way for me to tackle ALL the =
cool
places in SF (let alone anywhere else in the Bay).  I was wondering if =
any
of you would like to contribute to the site and write short articles on =
your
experiences where you go.  Heck, I'd even be able to make some phone =
calls
to people and see if I can get you guest list access if you're willing.

=20

I've spent a lot of hard working time into this site, and all I want to =
do
is have others enjoy the site as much as I do building to it.  So, if =
any of
you have a passion for electronic music like I do, shoot me an email.  =
I'd
love to hear from ya.  Thanks peeps!

=20

Patrick Morano

www.djunderground.com

=20

so i roll out to the spot, and we hop the railroad trax n shit and we start 
heading out there, and hella fucking fuzz stop us and check our eyes and shit. 
then we meet all these people chill under a bridge for hell of long, then we 
here its moved out to daly so we follow these crazy fire people out there, who 
by the way paid the bridge toll for me which i totally forgot to say thank you 
for, that was hella cool of you guys if u ever see this, happy and the otehr 
fire dancing chick, we get out to that spot in daly and walk days down this 
crazy ass trail and then we wait for a while they do a little fire crazy shit, 
which was hella entertaining. then i decided to bounce cause it was already 
2:30 and i had to drive all the way back to oakley. hope everything went well at 
the stables! super sorry about the fucking bust :( i heard that place was off 
the hizook. all in all a cool night   didnt get to catch any sets.... or any 
music other than the  radio and the cool girl with the flute under the bridge 
but met some hella coo peeps. glad i got outa the house :)

Hey, it's Sunday again.  That means it's time for DIRTBOX!  And goddamn,
do we have a show for you.

Jerel, Hooligan and myself (aka Partners in Crime) will be rockin out
alongside Shilow & Scandal from VA, DJ Alnie from NYC/MD, and Davey A & DJ
Random of WV.  These guys are all damn good DJs and cool people to boot.

Here are the tenative timeslots (times in EST, GMT-5):
07-08pm - Shilow & Scandal
08-09pm - ODJ
09-10pm - Hooligan
10-11pm - Jerel
11-12am - Alnie
12-??am - Afterhours w/ PiC, Davey A & DJ Random

All the links for the show are available at
http://dirtboxradio.com/listen.html, or below:

128k stream: http://64.246.60.15:8800/listen.pls
64k stream: http://jungletrain.net/64kbps.pls
24k stream: http://jungletrain.net/24kbps.pls

webcam: http://glue.umd.edu/~odjallen/dirtboxradio/webcam.html
chatroom: http://jungletrain.net/index.php?page=2&subpage=0&color=2
AIM: DIRTBOXRADIO

We're always looking for fresh talent to play the show, so hit us up if
you're interested.  We're primarily a drum 'n' bass station, but stray
occasionally for Breaks, Hip-Hop, etc.  Send an email to
bookme@dirtboxradio.com for more info.

Here's a sneak peak at our upcoming lineups:
3/14 - Glitchwillis, Lycan
3/21 - Ol Skool Night w/ John Tab, Locks, and Crucial Carl

4/04 - (tba)
4/18 - Dirtbox es Dos - dbox anniversary #2
4/25 - (tba)
5/02 - Breaks Night a'la Ian
5/09 - Winterman, Relapse

For up-to-date information, archives, photos, and more, check out our
website at http://dirtboxradio.com

Easy


Jackson aka ODJ

Subject: [sfraves] Bring back the PLUR!!!!

-------------------------------1078746535
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="US-ASCII"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

Do you remember the last time you heard the word PLUR? Do you remember when 
times were better? Back when it was REALLY all about the music? Do you remember 
when promoters actually gave a damn? When they cared about bringing you the 
best show instead of only looking to make a quick profit. Because of a few 
careless kids and a couple greedy promoters, our scene has changed so much. You 
are a part of new generation of party goers. You, while everyone has left the 
scene, have stood your ground and said "It still is all about the music." You 
have picked up the torch,  together we will see the scene evolve. United we will 
change the scene into something beautiful once again. To do this we must 
bring back the PLUR! because this was the foundation on which once brought us 
together in soulful unity. PLUR is not just a word, its a way of living. Maybe to 
some it sounds corny, but the fundamentals and simplicity are the beginnings 
of harmony with one another. This is our sacred escape from the daily rigors of 
life and stress. Our form of release by getting together with other people 
who feel the same way. We gather under the cover of night. We assemble in the 
most remote locations. We are all in unison as are bodies move to music which is 
not main stream. We don't care what others wear, or how they dance just as 
long as they come to celebrate life with us for one night under the stars. Don't 
you miss that? Help bring that vibrant feeling back again. Its up to us now 
to take a stand. Don't you want to be a part of the next movement, of something 
big again? 

Do what you can, get involved. Talk to your friends, Support the movement, 
Respect the scene, Show love to the newbies and pass this along to all your 
friends

oXoXoX Love all you guys XoXoXo

-------------------------------1078746535--

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="US-ASCII"

Yeah, but will Ortofons stay in the groove when you use them for serious 
scratching?  I use Shure M44-7s.

Frank


if anything everyone should learn how to raise/balance a tonearm and use 
anti-skate and everything else besides wayy before you rush out and get expensive 
needles. 

       In answer to your query, it doesn't really matter at all. it's a 
matter of style, brand loyalty, preference and money. it's not what your needle is 
or does, it's what you use it for and how you handle it. i've listed a ton of 
things on the defsf.com discussion board that you should consider before 
saying "my needle and cartridge suck". the list is pretty long. if you're truly 
interested in all of the technical aspects please set your URL to the following 
address to see the full disclosure additional comments and can be made in 
response there in the discussion forum:::
http://www.defsf.com/discussion/1078764088  
.

       the brands themselves each have their strengths and faults. i prefer 
the shure m447 cartridges and needles because the needles with proper care last 
twice as long as most needles. the sure's a pretty good investment for the 
needles due to their great durability. i myself have had the same set of needles 
for three years. and they still sound great but i have to clean them somewhat 
regularly. but rest assured, nothing sounds like a great new sure needle.
i also prefer the m447 cartridges because they are nice and loud. they have a 
fatty magnet in the cartridge pick-up that generates more initial gain in the 
signal before it can be processed. that leads to better amplification of 
quiet sounds and adds more dynamic expression to your scratching by picking up 
subtle gestures in your hands. it's almost like the cartridge is more quickly 
linked to your mind and your emotions at that time, and to have a giant massive 
soundsystem hooked up to that is a totally awe inspiring and orgasmic.
        aside from that, the cartridge tends to be  a bit bulky and wobbles 
under heavy handling. i rectify this by setting the cartridge in the headshell 
on the bias with the face of the needle (and adorable face mask) set 
perpendicularly to the root of the tone arm. this mimics a str8 arm turntable and helps 
alot with the wobbling.
       the ortophones are actually really decent for scratching yet remain a 
bit problematic to me. the needles sound pretty solid in the groove and hav e 
a certain je ne sais quoi about their tone that vibes me the right way. it's 
almost like listening to a good violinist. that's possibly due to their weight 
and being so nimble while set inside the notched cartridge. their design 
allows for the least wobbly of all the carts but usually they still have problems. 
like sometimes the little plastic arm is broken off or the rubber on the arm 
has fallen off. the needle can't be adjusted manually to get your own sound. 
although the headshell mounted versions are pretty choice... other times the 
needles are expensive, get lost easily, get stolen by jealous rivals that have 
lost theirs to theft, or get swallowed whole by small children as if they were 
candy. and that case is too prissy. `;P
       stantons are altogether the best start up cartridge and needle set. 
especially when talking about the 500al (?). the needles replace easily and 
cheaply and last a fair amount of time but can't last more than a year. the 
trackmaster series i don't trust too much because of the price and the really fake 
looking design. they look a bit booty and ghetto-fabulous to me. and really. 
how good can it be if one of their best versions is pink..? ortophone had it 
right with the royal blue.
       then again why are we talking needles here? because if the records 
didn't skip it wouldn't be an art. it takes knowledge and practice and dedication 
to source rare records and then to track that thin lined groove and make it 
sound musical and make the producers sound their best. we don't go to the net 
and rip and mix down 50 songs that everybody has heard already to your mp3 cd 
player for free and add that thin clear digital film to make the producers 
sound plastic. besides everybody knows if you own a pioneer mixer and two cdjs all 
you have to do is program a bunch of songs to play in sequence on the players 
and press the mix button on the mixer. i mean aren't robots being made to dj 
now just like robot bartenders are serving drinks in london? ... guess all 
that's another can of worms.
<(@)> <(@)>
\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/
-boo.
/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\


++spects++
-Sean Ocean-

mixtape ever. i don't suck as much as i did back then, and i
tweaked everything just so, in order to put them together
appropriately.

Hey everyone,

I just thought I'd give you all the heads up that we finally have received 
Resistance Recordings 004, the "RUN FOR THE BORDER EP", and Soupwarz 001 in 
stock. Both releases are bangin and we're extremely happy with them!

You can listen to and grab these releases at our online store:

http://www.resistancerecordings.com/storenew.html


Here's some info on the releases:


RES-004: DJ Junkinx | DJ Tronic - 'Run for the Border EP'
(includes: Wreck the Diskotek - Junkinx original + DJ Tronic remix, Let Da 
Boom, The Pain Train)
|| Fourth release from Resistance Recordings brings a new producer to the 
label, DJ Junkinx. Tracks are already being supported with top DJs having 
them in their rotations. Bangin' til the last beat, and a sure fire crowd 
favorite!


SOUP001: DJ Tronic | Carlos Alfonzo - 'Soupwarz001'  [LIMITED 10" WHITE
VINYL - 300 COPIES ONLY]
(includes: After Midnight, Pac This!, Spirit of SF, I Wish U Knew)
|| New sublabel of Resistance Recordings, this label vows to bring some fun 
back into music! AFTER MIDNIGHT is a huge crowd anthem, with plays all 
over the world and throughout the USA. DJ Tronic side features familiar 
blend of American Hard House/Hardcore and the Carlos Alfonzo side features a 
blend of funky house and techno.


You can check out the audio and grab these releases at our online store:

http://www.resistancerecordings.com/storenew.html

*Also, every order of SOUPWARZ 001 will receieve a very limited special CD! 
Our way of saying thanks for the support!*


Thank you for your support.. we hope you enjoy the new releases and keep 
bangin those hard beats!!

simon doesn't like to be noticed. it is not that he doesn't want to be known, but he knows that he is not actually being seen for himself, and it really gets on his nerves. when simon hangs out with john, everything is all good except for being "seen" and "heard". simon always regrets that people who "saw" and "heard" him are thinking of him as he reflects on moments past while he brushes his teeth the following day. it is worse than anyone's hangover, he believes. :)

Luna Lounge last week.  Crystal Method played the Warfield.  and Koma and 
Bones are playing Get Freaky at the end of the month.

not to mention that there is strong local break representation at several ug 
parties this month, including Moksha's 2 year and at Furious (mo' info to 
come on that one).

wowzers.

  *************PLEASE DO NOT POST TO OTHER LISTS***************


SATURDAY, March 20th
(The Spring Equinox)

10PM to 6:30 AM

In celebration of twenty years of house music
and two years of MOKSHA TRIBE parties
we are proud to bring you...

**CATCH 20-2**

"In the beginning there was Jack, and Jack had a groove..."

With special guests JESSE SAUNDERS!!! Using a blueprint of old school funk, 
disco, R&B, early pop and hip-hop, JESSE SAUNDERS is the architect of the 
musical style known as "House Music."  He wrote, produced and released the 
first documented House record titled "ON & ON" through his own label Jes 
Say Records.
And ADAM OHANA.  Adam Ohana has been DJing and producing electronic music 
for over 10 years under various monikers and has been an instrumental part 
of the underground music culture in SF.  Adam has recently been focusing 
his musical energies and talents on  breaks music as a medium to express 
his love for different styles.  Ohana has a variety of breaks releases 
scheduled under the name an.ten.nae, and is the force behind the amazing 
"Get Freaky" parties


Four full rooms of music with decorations and themes from past Moksha Tribe 
parties.
Come dressed as you did at your favorite Moksha event.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The Aboriginal Room:
House and Tech House
(in order of appearance)

Apollo  (Paradise Garage, founder of Moksha Tribe)
Origami  (Moksha Tribe, newstylesound)
Jesse Saunders (originator of house music, King Street/Broken Records, Sony 
Music)
DJ Amber (:CODE, SisterSF, Justsayagency)
DilemaFunk Doc (Moksha Tribe)

The Jagan Room:
Breaks, Tech House, Psytrance, Industrial

ShezTek (Moksha Tribe, Ambreaks, Evolving Spectrum Productions)
Adam Ohana (an-ten-nae, Get Freaky)
Shazbot (Moksha Tribe, newstylesound)
nomadic DJ (Moksha Tribe)
Marshal (Moksha Tribe, SWAT Sound)

The Deviance Room:
Breaks, Ghetto tech, Hip hop,
Ragga Jungle Dub Plate Business, Drum 'n' bass

Jauncy (Moksha Tribe)
Andy W (Resourcerecords, Refined Music, Viberation) with MC Boomerang 
Fidget (Ambient Mafia)
Koda (Urban Drums, Basedonbass.com, Owned Clothing)
The Doctor (BayRaves, Liquid Vinyl DJs)
Marcine (Moksha Tribe)

The Harvest Room:
Ambient beats, chill room

DV8 (Moksha Tribe, Evolving Spectrum Productions)
Red Stickman (Moksha Tribe, Ambient Mafia)
Calamity Jane (Moksha Tribe, Ambreaks)
V0lljude (Dub Beautiful Collective)
Brian Behlendorf (founder, sfraves)

Visuals by Viberation
Sound by SWAT

Convenient Bay Area underground location
18+

As always, you will be treated with love and respect and offered:

*Free Water
*Free fruit
*Free refreshments
*Free toys

Massages by Ravin' Riz to benefit Larkin Street

ALL PROFITS FROM THIS EVENT WILL BE DONATED TO LARKIN STREET YOUTH SERVICES

<http://www.larkinstreetyouth.org/>www.larkinstreetyouth.org

Very limited presale tickets are now available for $12.00 through these 
Moksha Tribe members:

PENINSULA :   Carl  650-851-9790 (nomadic@nomadicdj.com)
SOUTH BAY:  Terry  408-398-0593 (terry@viberation.com)
EAST BAY:  Shawn  415-577-3961 (shawn@alterior.net) evenings only
TREASURE ISLAND:  Shelley  415-982-0771 (scarpetta80@yahoo.com)
SAN FRANCISCO:  Leslie  415-425-5583 (leslieayres@hotmail.com)
or Apollo  415-564-4884 (apollo@speakeasy.org)

You can also purchase tickets through PayPal for $13.00 to cover 
transaction and mailing costs.
   Check our Catch 20-2 website

www.mokshatribe.org/catch22/

after Wednesday March 10th for Paypal purchases and party updates
or click on the Paypal button below.

All PayPal tickets purchased before Monday, March 15th, will be mailed to 
guests.
After the 15th, PayPal purchased tickets will be held at will call (PayPal 
receipt and ID required).

Selected Moksha Tribe members will have tickets for sale at
local parties this weekend.

Additional ticket purchase and other information will be posted to this list.

"Security is mostly a superstition.  It does not exist in nature, nor do 
the children of humans as a whole experience it.  Avoiding danger is no 
safer in the long run than outright exposure.  Life is either a daring 
adventure or nothing."
-Helen Keller

"What difference does it make to the dead, the orphans and the homeless, 
whether the mad destruction is wrought under the name of totalitarianism or 
the holy name of liberty or democracy?"
-Mahatma Gandhi

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Date: Wed, 10 Mar 2004 03:56:43 -0800
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII; format=flowed
Mime-Version: 1.0 (Apple Message framework v553)
From: Starchild <sfdreamer@earthlink.net>
To: SFraves@hyperreal.org
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Message-Id: <001115DD-728A-11D8-B54A-003065DA480A@earthlink.net>
X-Mailer: Apple Mail (2.553)
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] NRR:  60 Minutes II appearance tomorrow?

	I was headed down to City Hall to meet someone on an unrelated matter 
today, when he told me that a bunch of Christian anti-gay marriage 
protesters were just arriving. So I grabbed one of the signs we made to 
carry while handing out roses to the newlyweds on behalf of the 
Libertarian Party last week, and rushed down.

	Sure enough, about 30 or so people from the Fresno area were out front 
of City Hall with signs and a big banner reading "Homosexuality is a 
Sin," etc. One guy was carrying a big sign with a single word on it:  
"GROSS," which seemed oddly appropriate. Anyway, I got right in there 
with my sign, which said "Fight puritanism! Defend human rights!" on 
one side, and "Keep the State Out of Our Bedrooms" with the Statue of 
Liberty on the other. Speaking of which, my friend Denise happened to 
be there in a great Lady Liberty outfit handing out tax preparation 
discount coupons to gay couples on behalf of Liberty Tax Service. That 
probably didn't make the protesters too happy either.

	A bunch of them surrounded me, and we got into some intense debating 
before things mellowed out. At one point there were like three guys 
standing in front of me with their Bibles open, trying to read from 
different passages! Eventually a police officer took me by the arm and 
led me away from the group. Afterward I was able to have calm, polite 
discussions with several of them individually or in smaller groups. 
They didn't stick around very long; within a couple hours, the whole 
lot seemed to have cleared out, and even while they were there, 
newlywed couples coming out of City Hall were getting cheers and 
applause from other bystanders in the area. A number of these people 
expressed their appreciation to me and to Denise for being there, or 
came up to talk to us.

	But the initial confrontational nature of the exchange provided some 
terrific photo ops, and there were a number of people taking pictures. 
I was interviewed and filmed by a couple students from the Broadcasting 
department at SF State, and talked to a reporter from the Examiner (Joe 
Manio). I also gave my name and information to a photographer from the 
Chronicle, but on the condition that he include the information that I 
was with the Libertarian Party -- last week my roommate Raphael and I 
got quoted in the paper, but they neglected to mention the LP despite 
the fact that we told the reporter that we were there on behalf of the 
party for the rose action previously noted, gave him a card, he saw the 
signs, etc., and simply reported us as bystanders rather than 
protesters.

	Anyway, the most promising development of the day came when someone 
told me near the end that CBS 60 Minutes II had been there, and that 
one of the guys with the crew had said it was some of the better 
footage they'd gotten and they'd be sending it in. Allegedly there is 
some chance of it being on the air tomorrow evening -- I haven't 
checked the broadcast schedule, and don't know if this information is 
reliable, but you might keep an eye out for it.

Yours in liberty,
						<<< Starchild >>>

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Flying with records...

If you have a lock on your check-in, they will cut it off to see what's 
inside. They now have the right to, and are supposed to. I always have two 
separate crates/bags. I check in an unlocked crate with all my new easy to 
obtain/easily replaced records. I figure if they get lost, when I'm in the 
local record shop, I'll try to replace some of them if possible. The secret 
gems and whites I carry on with me, along with my headphones and CDRs. You 
may get pulled out of line, you will almost definately get questioned at the 
x-ray scanner because vinyl comes up round and black and they can't see thru 
it, they usually open it open and look inside, but hardly ever any hassles. 
It's become pretty routine.. Besides when you split up your crate, your 
carry-on bag is much lighter, if you try to carry on all your vinyl, you get 
that aching back syndrome, because of course, your layovers are all the way 
on the other side of the terminal, every damn time.

Only chime in on topics I know...

-JH

break from party production. If you want to attend Passion Fish, please
respond and I'll help you purchase a ticket.

ASR presents Passion Fish
March 13, 2004
Bay Area Underground Location

Bryan Zentz AKA Barada (Soma/Intec/Disruptor; Santini)

March 13th.

take care,

Friends,

This Wednesday evening, Students for Sensible Drug Policy and DanceSafe 
will be premiering "Generation E," a documentary about the RAVE Act, 
the attack on youth culture, and the war on drugs.

When: Wednesday, March 10 at 7:000 p.m.

Where: 2050 Valley Life Sciences Building on the UC Berkeley Campus

Admission: $5 donation requested - nobody will be turned away for lack 
of funds

Arrive early if you can because Judge James Gray will be speaking from 
6-7 in the same room - he is the author of "Why Our Drug Laws Have 
Failed and What We Can Do About It" and is running for US Senate.

Please join us and bring all your friends!

For more info, email me or visit our website - 
www.drugresourcecenter.org

-Rebecca Saltzman

Drug Resource Center

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

Punk veteran dies in his sleep

John McGeoch, a veteran of the British punk movement, has died at the age 
of 48.

The guitarist, who co-founded Manchester band Magazine and later played 
with Souxsie and the Banshees and John Lydon's Public Image Limited, died 
in his sleep.

Banshees' bass player Steven Severin confirmed the news on his website and 
added: "Deepest sympathies to those close to him."

McGeoch's distinctive guitar sound featured on the Banshees' hits Happy 
House, Christine and Spellbound.

He played on three PiL albums, 1987's Happy?, 1989's Public Image Ltd, and 
1992's That What Is Not. He also worked with former Bauhaus singer Pete 
Murphy, Generation X, Visage and Ultravox.

The guitarist, born in Greenock, Scotland, moved to Los Angeles in 1986, 
but returned to Britain in the 90s. In the early 90s he worked with Heaven 
17's Glenn Gregory.

By 1995 he had become a qualified nurse and given up performing although he 
continued to work on music for TV.



Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org
                 http://mokshatribe.org/photos/

ILLFORMANTS (Breakbeat Science, Subtitles)
Recording separately as Controlled Substance and Angel
Zero, this duo have turned heads in recent years with
stormers such as The Bizarre. Their fresh take on
techstep is characterized by crisp beats and sci-fi
sound effects rolling out over deep deadly basslines.
Expect another storming B2B set from these Bay Area
favorites!

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Flying with records...

Ya, I flew back from Phoenix a month ago, and after running my backpack 
record bag through the x-ray, I got pulled aside. The security guy asked 
me if there is something round in there, and I said, "Um, my 
headphones?" He said "No, this is large." I told him that the bag was 
filled with records, and his face lit up. "Vinyl?" he asked. He flipped 
through all the records to make sure there wasn't anything hidden in the 
middle and then bade me a good flight. It only took about a minute 
total, so I didn't mind at all, but yes, you should expect to be 
questioned.

Happy

Secret Society wrote:

> If you have a lock on your check-in, they will cut it off to see what's 
> inside. They now have the right to, and are supposed to. I always have 
> two separate crates/bags. I check in an unlocked crate with all my new 
> easy to obtain/easily replaced records. I figure if they get lost, when 
> I'm in the local record shop, I'll try to replace some of them if 
> possible. The secret gems and whites I carry on with me, along with my 
> headphones and CDRs. You may get pulled out of line, you will almost 
> definately get questioned at the x-ray scanner because vinyl comes up 
> round and black and they can't see thru it, they usually open it open 
> and look inside, but hardly ever any hassles. It's become pretty 
> routine.. Besides when you split up your crate, your carry-on bag is 
> much lighter, if you try to carry on all your vinyl, you get that aching 
> back syndrome, because of course, your layovers are all the way on the 
> other side of the terminal, every damn time.
> 
> Only chime in on topics I know...
>

request

A little over a month ago I began a project with two friends to alter the 
November 2004 election.

We believe we have developed an extraordinary plan to register 1 million 
voters before the end of the year!

Our plan is to create and implement a web-based voter registration tool, 
with a unique viral marketing program, focused on registering college 
students and under-represented communities. We expect this site to launch 
in just about 5-6 weeks from now.

In order to jumpstart this program, we are in need of approximately $25,000 
to start. While we do have a working plan to generate money from foundation 
grants and other sources, we are at the stage where we need at least two of 
us to be working full-time on this project immediately, in order to reach 
our goal.

Currently we are applying for our non-profit status, and mobilizing a large 
amount of volunteers. One generous supporter has already donated office 
space for us in San Francisco, and our web developer team has already begun 
to design the site.

In order for me to commit full-time on this project, I will need to 
generate $6000 in the next two weeks which will source two months of my 
full-time employment on this project.

I have never been more certain, or more passionate, about the possibly of 
what we are creating here. (next to Radiance, of course!) But, in order for 
me to really make this a reality, I am going to need your generous help!

I am requesting a donation, however much you can contribute, to make this 
happen. Every $25, $50, $100 and $500 donation will pave the way for me to 
create the job of my dreams, and transform American politics.

I have opened my 
<https://www.paypal.com/xclick/business=aaron%40pava.com&item_name=Aaron%27s%2BJustVote.org%2BFund&no_note=1&tax=0cy_code=USD&lc=US>PayPal 
account in order to immediately receive donations of any amount.

<https://www.paypal.com/xclick/business=aaron%40pava.com&item_name=Aaron%27s%2BJustVote.org%2BFund&no_note=1&tax=0cy_code=USD&lc=US>Click 
here to DONATE NOW!

I realize this is a bold request and I want you to know that I honor you 
whether you are able to make a donation at this time or not. If you can 
help, I promise to do everything in my power to make the Bay Area dance 
community proud and be unstoppable on this mission!

Thank you for your trust, love and support,
Aaron

p.s. In a week or so, I will send out an email announcing the success of 
this drive. I will also be preparing a more detailed description of the 
project itself and our plan of action. If you interested in supporting the 
project in some way, please <mailto:aaron@pava.com>let me know!

p.p.s. Also, I have also started a Topica list to make it easier to stay in 
communication with you. Please take a moment to send a blank email to 
<mailto:aaronsbroadcast-subscribe@topica.com>aaronsbroadcast-subscribe@topica.com 
to join this list. (even if you can't contribute now, I can keep you in the 
loop of the project!) Thanks!

On Wed, 10 Mar 2004, Apollo wrote:
-&e->Punk veteran dies in his sleep
-&e->
-&e->John McGeoch, a veteran of the British punk movement, has died at the age
-&e->of 48.
-&e->
-&e->The guitarist, who co-founded Manchester band Magazine and later played
-&e->with Souxsie and the Banshees and John Lydon's Public Image Limited, died
-&e->in his sleep.
-&e->
-&e->Banshees' bass player Steven Severin confirmed the news on his website and
-&e->added: "Deepest sympathies to those close to him."
-&e->
-&e->McGeoch's distinctive guitar sound featured on the Banshees' hits Happy
-&e->House, Christine and Spellbound.
-&e->
-&e->He played on three PiL albums, 1987's Happy?, 1989's Public Image Ltd, and
-&e->1992's That What Is Not. He also worked with former Bauhaus singer Pete
-&e->Murphy, Generation X, Visage and Ultravox.
-&e->
-&e->The guitarist, born in Greenock, Scotland, moved to Los Angeles in 1986,
-&e->but returned to Britain in the 90s. In the early 90s he worked with Heaven
-&e->17's Glenn Gregory.
-&e->
-&e->By 1995 he had become a qualified nurse and given up performing although he
-&e->continued to work on music for TV.
-&e->
-&e->
-&e->
-&e->Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org
-&e->                 http://mokshatribe.org/photos/

Subject: Re: [sfraves] HELP! Audio question

soundforge 6 is kind of a useful tool with tracks n cd's n such. You can rip
the music from the cd as a single file, or multiple trax and save it pretty
much however you want to. It's also pretty easy to burn cd's.

www.kazaa.com is a peer2peer network sharing resource kinda thing. . .

you can pretty much find and music program, graph program, game, horse-porn
or underage whatever with it. It does open your computer up to all sorts of
security and virus issues tho.

aK

Subject: [sfraves] (bsp) Booty, Breaks and Balaclavas - Friday, March 12

BOOTY, BREAKS AND BALACLAVAS

Outdoor DJ area at the 7th Annual Anarchist Cafe

featuring DJs Tomkat (Subversive Soundz, SPAZ), Morse
Code (Subversive Soundz) and J. Clang (Havoc)

booty, breaks, techno, downtempo, plus

Friday, March 12, 2004
entire event: 6pm to midnight
DJs and dancing: 9:30pm to midnight

at "The Kitchen"
225 Portrero Ave., at 16th Street
San Francisco

A benefit for The Bay Area Anarchist Bookfair
and political prisoner Sherman Austin 

$5 - $15 donation requested
No one turned away for lack of funds

INDOOR PERFORMANCE AREA including
music, guest speakers, spoken word, and poetry

"BOOTY, BREAKS AND BALACLAVAS" 
OUTDOOR DJ AREA by Subversive Soundz 
 
VIDEO by Video Activist Network 

dinner 6:30
performers indoors 7-10
video 8-9
DJs and dancing 9:30 til midnight

all ages!  kid friendly!

drug and alcohol free space.
wheelchair accessible.   

The Bay Area Anarchist Bookfair, now in its ninth
year, takes places on Saturday, March 13 from 10am to
6pm at the S.F. County Fair Building on 9th Avenue in
Golden Gate Park.  Admission is free, and speakers
include Starhawk, Alexander Cockburn, Jeffrey St.
Clair, Lynn Breedlove, TimM T. West, Katya Komisaruk,
Agent Apple of the Biotic Baking Brigade, Susan
Greene, Sun Frog and Sean Sullivan.  For more
information call (415) 431-8355.

Sherman Austin, a 20 year-old, black, Southern
California anarchist, was the webmaster of the site
www.raisethefist.com. He is the first person to be
charged under 18 U.S.C. 842(p), a 1997
"anti-terrorism" law authored by California Senator
Dianne Feinstein.  What was Austins crime?  He had
had offered free hosting and a link on his website to
a site called The Reclaim Guide, offering general
security culture information along with a small
portion dealing with explosives, authored by a young
white person from a wealthy, conservative family. 
This information is publicly available, and Austin
merely linked to it, yet he is being jailed for it.  

On August 4, Sherman Austin was sentened to one year
in federal prison and three years probation.  His
probation includes the following terms: Austin cannot
possess or access a computer of any kind without prior
approval of his probation officer; if he gets that
approval, the equipment is subject to monitoring and
to search and seizure at any time, without notice; he
must surrender his phone, DSL, electric, and satellite
bills to his probation officer; and he cannot
associate with any person or group--environmental,
social justice, political, or economic--that seeks to
change the government in any way.

Although Austin initially planned to fight the charge
and go to trial, he accepted a plea bargain after
being threatened with serving up to 20 years in jail.
Despite both the FBI and the Justice Department
agreeing on a sentence of four months in jail and four
months in community confinement, the judge increased
the sentence to set an example for future
"revolutionaries."  


For more information about Sherman Austin, please see:

www.freesherman.org
http://www.counterpunch.org/merlin08162003.html
http://rwor.org/a/1217/austin.htm
http://www.infoshop.org/shermanaustin.html

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Flying with records...

This has happened to me too.  The reason they questioned me was because a bunch 
of vinyl together is very dense, and it appears on the x-ray as a big square 
black blob that can't be penetrated by the machine.  I did the same thing-- 
opened the bag, took out some vinyl, and they were happy and let me go on my 
way.

Frank

Quoting Happy <happy@cannabass.com>:

> Ya, I flew back from Phoenix a month ago, and after running my backpack 
> record bag through the x-ray, I got pulled aside. The security guy asked 
> me if there is something round in there, and I said, "Um, my 
> headphones?" He said "No, this is large." I told him that the bag was 
> filled with records, and his face lit up. "Vinyl?" he asked. He flipped 
> through all the records to make sure there wasn't anything hidden in the 
> middle and then bade me a good flight. It only took about a minute 
> total, so I didn't mind at all, but yes, you should expect to be 
> questioned.

> Secret Society wrote:
> 
> > If you have a lock on your check-in, they will cut it off to see what's 
> > inside. They now have the right to, and are supposed to. I always have 
> > two separate crates/bags. I check in an unlocked crate with all my new 
> > easy to obtain/easily replaced records. I figure if they get lost, when 
> > I'm in the local record shop, I'll try to replace some of them if 
> > possible. The secret gems and whites I carry on with me, along with my 
> > headphones and CDRs. You may get pulled out of line, you will almost 
> > definately get questioned at the x-ray scanner because vinyl comes up 
> > round and black and they can't see thru it, they usually open it open 
> > and look inside, but hardly ever any hassles. It's become pretty 
> > routine.. Besides when you split up your crate, your carry-on bag is

>>> If you have a lock on your check-in, they will cut it off to see  
>>> what's
>>> inside. They now have the right to, and are supposed to. I always  
>>> have

>>> my

Hello 2day... but i still dunno what this class is about!

OK... I'm like Hugger-Mugger right now... I should get off the computer... LoL

overheard at checkpoint alpha:
Mister W, is it or is it not true that you claimed you would be "dropping
the bomb" on your next booking in an email commmuncation with our
promoter/informant?  These "killer tracks", what kind of range do you
estimate they have?  And what of these bass hits that will make people as
you stated "shit their pants and question their faith"... is it possible
they could have more severe effects at higher volumes?

went to canada late last year... didn't pack vinyl but it's not so bad
(just remember with the international, if you are making money on a
booking get a work visa... stupid but true).

oh, and the average sized record flight box fits under seat (you don't
have to check it as luggage).  you can usually get away with a light
backpack (overhead) + a box like that underseat.  worst case it gets
packed as late luggage which means it's first off the plane.  yay!

andyw

But yield who will to their separation
My object in living is to unite
My avocation and my vocation
As my two eyes make one in sight.
Only where love and need are one,
And the work is play for mortal stakes,
Is the deed ever really done
For Heaven and future's sakes.
Robert Frost

Friday, March 12, 2004 ** Booty, Breaks and Balaclavas **

BOOTY, BREAKS AND BALACLAVAS

Outdoor DJ area at the Anarchist Cafe

featuring DJs Tomkat, Morse Code and J. Clang
booty, breaks, techno, plus

This is part of the Anarchist Cafe, a benefit for the Anarchist Bookfair an=
d anarchist political prisoner Sherman Austin

There will be a vegan dinner and performers inside, video, DJs and dancing =
outside.


$5 - $15 donation requested
No one turned away for lack of funds

dinner 6:30
performers indoors 7-10
video 8-9
dancing 9 =91til midnight

all ages!  kid friendly!

drug and alcohol free space.
wheelchair accessible.


The Bay Area Anarchist Bookfair, now in its ninth year, takes places on Sat=
urday, March 13 from 10am to 6pm at the S.F. County Fair Building on 9th Av=
enue in Golden Gate Park.  Admission is free, and speakers include Starhawk=
, Alexander Cockburn, Jeffrey St. Clair, Lynn Breedlove, Tim=92M T. West, K=
atya Komisaruk, Agent Apple of the Biotic Baking Brigade, Susan Greene, Sun=
 Frog and Sean Sullivan.  For more information call (415) 431-8355.

Sherman Austin, a 20 year-old, black, Southern California anarchist, was th=
e webmaster of the site www.raisethefist.com. He is the first person to be =
charged under 18 U.S.C. 842(p), a 1997 "anti-terrorism" law authored by Cal=
ifornia Senator Dianne Feinstein.  What was Austin=92s crime?  He had had o=
ffered free hosting and a link on his website to a site he did not author c=
alled The Reclaim Guide, offering general security culture information alon=
g with a small portion dealing with explosives.  This information is public=
ly available, yet Austin has been jailed for merely linking to it.

On August 4, Sherman Austin was sentened to one year in federal prison and =
three years probation.  His probation includes the following terms: Austin =
cannot possess or access a computer of any kind without prior approval of h=
is probation officer; if he gets that approval, the equipment is subject to=
 monitoring and to search and seizure at any time, without notice; he must =
surrender his phone, DSL, electric, and satellite bills to his probation of=
ficer; and he cannot associate with any person or group--environmental, soc=
ial justice, political, or economic--that seeks to change the government in=
 any way.

Although Austin initially planned to fight the charge and go to trial, he a=
ccepted a plea bargain after being threatened with serving up to 20 years i=
n jail. Despite both the FBI and the Justice Department agreeing on a sente=
nce of four months in jail and four months in community confinement, the ju=
dge increased the sentence to set an example for future "revolutionaries."


For more information about Sherman Austin, please see:

www.freesherman.org
http://www.counterpunch.org/merlin08162003.html
http://rwor.org/a/1217/austin.htm
http://www.infoshop.org/shermanaustin.html

http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf/calendar2/events/view?identifier=3D1147
San Francisco California, USA

Saturday, March 13, 2004 ** (((thump))) COSMOSIS returns to SF **

Saturday, March 13th
(((THUMP))) presented by Thump Radio

DJ's:
In the main room:
Pioneers of the bouncy bumpin' bassline groove, Cosmosis will unleash the b=
ass on San Francisco
*COSMOSIS (((Transient/Phantasm/Mumbo Jumbo/Turbo Trance)))
*TREVOR (((MoonTribe - LA)))
*KEPI (((Thump/MoonTribe - SF)))

Upstairs chillzone:
Peek (((Thump Radio)))
Saturnia (((Phoenix Family)))
Sinkus (((Thump Chill)))
Fiddler (((Thump Radio)))

Musical Style:  Trance and Chill

Cover: $20, before 11pm $15

Ambiance: Decor will be your favorite Thump style, Visuals by Dr. Spook, St=
ring Geometry by Andres and alter centerpiece by Akasha

Little side story: May 2002 I missed (((THUMP))) while attending a 3 day do=
uble wedding cruise for two different family members.  As you can imagine, =
the music on the cruise was seriously lacking.  While lamenting to a barten=
der about the music onboard vs. what I was missing at home, I learned that =
the bartender, Leon from South Africa, had been psytrance DJ in South Afric=
a for many years before signing up to bartend on the cruise ship.  I was th=
e first person in 10 months that he'd been able to chat with about music an=
d knew what the hell he was talking about.  He gave me his top 3 acts to ca=
tch when I could, one of which was Cosmosis.  To my surprise and excitement=
 upon my return home from the cruise I discovered that Cosmosis was the hea=
dliner for the next month, June of 2002!!  I danced my ass off at (((THUMP)=
)) June 2002, making up for the month I missed and simply because you just =
can't sit still with Cosmosis.  Simply not to be missed!!  Wear something c=
omfortable and plan on dancing til dawn or beyond!!

Wendsday, March 17. St. Patricks Day -  COMPRESSION INDUSTRIES & BLASHAUS i=
n association with FUTURE PRIMITIVE SOUND present The West Coast Debut of T=
he UK Mercury Prize Winning Artist DIZZEE RASCAL.

When Mike Skinner aka The Streets was asked, "what is  the future?", he sim=
ply replied replied,  "Dizzee Rascal". 18 years of age and hailing from Eas=
t London, Dizzee's unique hybrid of hip-hop, drum & bass and UK garage coup=
led with his explosive real-life tales of street crime,
poverty, sex and guns, are a combination unlike any MC we've heard --- unde=
rground or over. Alongside' peers including Roll Deep Crew, Heartless Crew,=
 Nasty Crew, More Fire Crew, and a handful of others, Dizzee has
forged the new sound of inner city London.  Boy In Da Corner' has been a ma=
jor UK hit since its release last summer, and this past September, Dizzee w=
as awarded the UK's Mercury Music Prize, beating out the likes of
Coldplay, Radiohead and the Darkness. Dizzee has been hailed as "the most o=
riginal and exciting artist to emerge from dance music in a decade" (Alex P=
etridas, The Guardian), the NME's Louis Pattison calling 'Boy In Da
Corner', "one of the most assured debut albums of the last five years." Alo=
ngside:  MARGA MAN & DJ SLIMZEE

With local support from: GOLD CHAINS, DALY SITUATIONS feat. UFO!

Artwork by: BUDER (ICP, TMF, FPS).  Hosted by: THE COMPRESSION SOUNDSYSTEM =

> -&e->>> filled with records, and his face lit up. "Vinyl?" he asked. He
> -&e->>> flipped
> -&e->>> through all the records to make sure there wasn't anything hidden in
> -&e->>> the
> -&e->>> middle and then bade me a good flight. It only took about a minute
> -&e->>> total, so I didn't mind at all, but yes, you should expect to be
> -&e->>> questioned.
> -&e->>>
> -&e->>> Happy
> -&e->>>
> -&e->>> Secret Society wrote:
> -&e->>>
> -&e->>>> If you have a lock on your check-in, they will cut it off to see
> -&e->>>> what's
> -&e->>>> inside. They now have the right to, and are supposed to. I always
> -&e->>>> have
> -&e->>>> two separate crates/bags. I check in an unlocked crate with all my
> -&e->>>> new
> -&e->>>> easy to obtain/easily replaced records. I figure if they get lost,
> -&e->>>> when
> -&e->>>> I'm in the local record shop, I'll try to replace some of them if
> -&e->>>> possible. The secret gems and whites I carry on with me, along with
> -&e->>>> my
> -&e->>>> headphones and CDRs. You may get pulled out of line, you will almost
> -&e->>>> definately get questioned at the x-ray scanner because vinyl comes up
> -&e->>>> round and black and they can't see thru it, they usually open it open
> -&e->>>> and look inside, but hardly ever any hassles. It's become pretty
> -&e->>>> routine.. Besides when you split up your crate, your carry-on bag is
> -&e->>>> much lighter, if you try to carry on all your vinyl, you get that
> -&e->>>> aching
> -&e->>>> back syndrome, because of course, your layovers are all the way on
> -&e->>>> the
> -&e->>>> other side of the terminal, every damn time.
> -&e->>>>
> -&e->>>> Only chime in on topics I know...
> -&e->>>>
> -&e->>>> -JH
> -&e->>>>
> -&e->>>>

Subject: [sfraves] ASR review

that was a tight little tekno party.  i kept hearing "i don't really 
like tekno, but this music is kicking my ass!" and other words to that 
effect.

i wasn't planning to go to this one, but a last-minute call from 
Matt-Jakes-with-an-extra-ticket got me dressed and ready to go in 
minutes.  i'm glad i went.

i used to wonder, "what's the big deal about ernie deaks?"  now i know. 
Jam & Spoon "Stella" at +10 or so, mixed into a tekno set?  i lost it - 
totally fucking brilliant!

thanks all for a great event. too bad it was at the TL.

-philip-

Subject: Re: [sfraves] ASR review

That and hearing Timo Maas - OCB in that same set... I kept thinking - *This
is supposed to be a techno set right??* I officially dub the sound I heard
that night as Progressive Techno. I'm not complaining. I liked what I heard,
but it was far from what I expected to hear. More Pascal FEOS type stuff
(that I've heard).

Great party. Great family reunion type of event. After a day boarding in
tahoe (70+ degrees!!) I was tired, but the loungey social nature of the
party suited my mood. I also don't think I've ever seen that space decked
out to that degree before. Things never got super packed inside either.
That's always a nice treat.

It was great to see a lot of people in fine drunk form. It was equally fun
to see as many people that dropped out of things a while ago back under the
same roof again (remember ninjax213@aol.com??). Just a great end to a long
day and a good party to press pause on party shit for a while on.

Good job ASR =)

:: r y a n ::

SATURDAY, March 20th
(The Spring Equinox)

10PM to 6:30 AM

In celebration of twenty years of house music
and two years of MOKSHA TRIBE parties
we are proud to bring you...

**CATCH 20-2**

"In the beginning there was Jack, and Jack had a groove..."

With special guest JESSE SAUNDERS!!! Using a blueprint of old school funk, 
disco, R&B, early pop and hip-hop, JESSE SAUNDERS is the architect of the 
musical style known as "House Music."  He wrote, produced and released the 
first documented House record titled "ON & ON" through his own label Jes 
Say Records.

Four full rooms of music with decorations and themes from past Moksha Tribe 
parties.
Come dressed as you did at your favorite Moksha event.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

House and Tech House

Music)

Subject: [sfraves] Not an ASR review (Seekr vs. DVS Minds instead)

------=_NextPart_000_0027_01C40A8D.574199C0
Content-Type: text/plain;
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

Hmmm, party peeps, I had a good Saturday night dancing at Drama, =
presented by Seekr and DVS Minds. It was like a battle of the DJ crews, =
in a tag-team setup, and it was great diversity in music. I wore myself =
out, totally. Didn't make it all night.=20

Ran into Marshall inside, the sound guru. He's a great guy, one of my =
favorite audiophiles. He seemed very concerned about sound quality but =
it was excellent to me ( that is, loud and booming).

Also saw Tyler, another great dude. Didn't get to talk to anyone much =
because it was all held in one big room (no chill area). But that's =
fine, I just wanted to dance. And they had big comfy couches lined up =
against the wall--this was where people were relaxing while watching the =
dancers.

The decoration theme was "us vs. them" which means it followed the =
tag-team concept (the DJ battle) and you were supposed to wear the =
button of your fave crew, and also vote for your favorite set with giant =
cut-out arrows (kind of like the "one way" road signs), so I guess you =
could point it up or down (or sideways!) to vote.

I am not sure if the crowd was into participating much but they sure =
liked the music, as did I. And that's what it's all about, anyway.=20

I was recognized, as usual, by my presence on the floor. This girl from =
the crew thanked me for coming out and she said that I always show my =
support. So I felt good about that. And another guy asked me if I liked =
the decorations and of course I said that I loved them, especially the =
black-light art and a sculpture of god-knows-what hanging on the wall.

I think this must be a backup venue for whomever has the cash because it =
was kind of nice (carpet, bathroom, bar, etc). It was a large room, too, =
so it seemed to hold the sound.

Overall, a good party, but I can't wait until the Moksha tribe event at =
an undisclosed location. See ya'll there.

Greg VP


------=_NextPart_000_0027_01C40A8D.574199C0--

Subject: Re: [sfraves] ASR review

I remember you saying that. The *progressive* term has a certain connotation
to it (not always a good one, especially in techno circles). Thing is that I
wouldn't call what I heard anything close to what house music is. I know
you're just trying to avoid the *progressive* term, but given that it's not
house, not trance, and not really what I'm used to hearing as *techno* the
progressive modifier is the only accurate term to stick on it.

Seems like some techno people out there are playing the game of *lesser of
two evils* Would I rather be associated with house or progressive(trance)? I
would think most would definitely gravitate towards the house designation
and thus the mis-classification.

:: r y a n ::

Subject: [sfraves] seeking help from DJ's and people who do sound equipment & lighting

-------------------------------1079398143
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="US-ASCII"

What's going on ? Well, the time is coming when the sun stays out more. When 
the party keeps on rocking late into the warm nights in CA. When it's safe to 
run around outside shirtless or nude. Well OK, on to the idea. 

I am seeking help from DJ's and people who do sound equipment & lighting. If 
you are a DJ or a sound/lighting person, please get back to me. I could use 
you & your help for something sick, twisted & very fun. I am trying to keep the 
budget low cost & pretty much free for the love. (P.L.U.R) well here is your 
(P.L.U.R) 

For those people willing to respond to me, I will key you in on this idea. 
Until then, it is a top secret plan to rave the weekend all night long, 
shirtless & wet. 

i am seeking DJ's of these styles:
House, Nrg/Trance, Hard-core/happy, Drum & bass, Chill out, Acid House, Euro 
Dance, Techno, Breaks, Progressive & all around dance music. 

For lighting i am seeking help with :
Fog, Lasers, Strobes, Visuals & art work (glow in the dark and trippy)

For sound i am seeking help with: 
good system willing to be heard both outdoors & indoors, able to play loud 
enough for 100+ people dancing around like wild monkeys 

I hope to see a lot of people willing to give myself some help, and I can 
work with you in any way, shape, or style. This will be something worthwhile, and 
I hope to see a lot of people having fun helping me out.

Thanks a lot for taking the time to read this !

please respond back to me @ djbigdaddyg@aol.com & positiveflowca@hotmail.com 
please send your e-mails to both e-mails thanks


-warren 
Daddy G DJ 
positive flow ca & Rave_One

-------------------------------1079398143--

Subject: [sfraves] Re: will a 4am last call kill the underground?

	My feeling is that bars shouldn't be denied the right to stay open 
until 4am just because a few bad apples among them might rat on 
underground parties to the cops. That would be no different from 
denying people the right to throw undergrounds just because of a few 
unethical promoters. If we want to stay true to the spirit of letting 
people do their own thing, and maintaining unity within the electronic 
dance community, it's a risk we have to take.

	Of course we should also demand an end to parties being busted just 
because they haven't paid their extortion money (aka permit fee) to the 
government.

Groove on,
					<<< Starchild >>>

Subject: [sfraves] (NRR) FBI pushes for broadband wiretap powers

--Apple-Mail-2-189505112
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable
Content-Type: text/plain;
	charset=ISO-8859-1;
	format=flowed

FBI pushes for broadband wiretap powers
ISPs, Net phone services would all have to rewire
By Ben Charny
March 12, 2004

A far-reaching proposal from the FBI, made public Friday, would require=20=

all broadband Internet providers, including cable modem and DSL=20
companies, to rewire their networks to support easy wiretapping by=20
police.

The FBI's request to the Federal Communications Commission aims to give=20=

police ready access to any form of Internet-based communications. If=20
approved as drafted, the proposal could dramatically expand the scope=20
of the agency's wiretap powers, raise costs for cable broadband=20
companies and complicate Internet product development.

Legal experts said the 85-page filing includes language that could be=20
interpreted as forcing companies to build backdoors into everything=20
from instant messaging and voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) programs=20=

to Microsoft's Xbox Live gaming service. The introduction of new=20
services that did not support a back door for police would be outlawed,=20=

and companies would be given 15 months to make sure existing services=20
comply.

"The importance and the urgency of this task cannot be overstated,"=20
says the proposal, which is also backed by the U.S. Department of=20
Justice and the Drug Enforcement Administration.

"The ability of federal, state and local law enforcement to carry out=20
critical electronic surveillance is being compromised today."

Because the eavesdropping scheme has the support of the Bush=20
administration, the FCC is expected to take it very seriously. Last=20
month, FCC Chairman Michael Powell stressed that "law enforcement=20
access to IP-enabled communications is essential" and police must have=20=

"access to communications infrastructure they need to protect our=20
nation."

The request from federal police comes almost a year after=20
representatives from the FBI's Electronic Surveillance Technology=20
Section approached the FCC and asked that broadband providers be=20
required to provide more efficient, standardized surveillance=20
facilities. Such new rules were necessary, the FBI argued, because=20
terrorists could otherwise frustrate legitimate wiretaps by placing=20
phone calls over the Internet.

"It is a very big deal and will be very costly for the Internet and the=20=

deployment of new technologies," said Stewart Baker, who represents=20
Internet providers as a partner at the Steptoe and Johnson law firm.=20
"Law enforcement is very serious about it. There is a lot of emotion=20
behind this. They have stories that they're very convinced about in=20
which they have not achieved access to communications and in which=20
wiretaps have failed."

Broadband in the mix
Broadband providers say the FBI's request would, for the first time,=20
force cable providers that sell broadband to come under the=20
jurisdiction of 1994's Communications Assistance for Law Enforcement=20
Act (CALEA), which further defined the already existing statutory=20
obligations of telecommunications carriers to help police conduct=20
electronic surveillance. Telephone companies that use their networks to=20=

sell broadband have already been following CALEA rules.

"For cable companies, it's all new," said Bellsouth spokesman Bill=20
McCloskey.

Several cable providers, including Comcast Communications, Time Warner=20=

Cable and Cablevision had no immediate comment on the FBI's request.

The FBI proposal would also force Vonage, 8x8, AT&T and other prominent=20=

providers of broadband telephone services to comply with CALEA.=20
Executives from these companies have said in the past that they all=20
intend to comply with any request law enforcement makes, if technically=20=

possible.

Broadband phone service providers say they are already creating a code=20=

of conduct to cover some of the same issues addressed by the FBI, but=20
on a voluntary basis, according to Jeff Pulver, founder of Free World=20
Dialup.

"We have our chance right now to prove to law enforcement that we can=20
do this on a voluntary basis," Pulver said. "If we mandate and make=20
rules, it will just complicate things."

Under CALEA, police must still follow legal procedures when wiretapping=20=

Internet communications. Depending on the situation, such wiretaps do=20
not always require court approval, in part because of changes to=20
wiretapping laws made by the USA Patriot Act.

A Verizon representative said Friday that the company has already=20
complied with at least one law enforcement request to tap a DSL line.

This week's proposal surprised privacy advocates by reaching beyond=20
broadband providers to target companies that offer communications=20
applications such as instant messaging clients.

"I don't think it's a reasonable claim," said Marc Rotenberg, director=20=

of the Electronic Privacy Information Center. "The FCC should seriously=20=

consider where the FBI believes its authority ... to regulate new=20
technologies would end. What about Bluetooth and USB?"

Baker agrees that the FBI's proposal means that IP-based services such=20=

as chat programs and videoconferencing "that are 'switched' in any=20
fashion would be treated as telephony."

If the FCC agrees, Baker said, "you would have to vet your designs with=20=

law enforcement before providing your service. There will be a queue.=20
There will be politics involved. It would completely change the way=20
services are introduced on the Internet."

As encryption becomes glued into more and more VoIP and instant=20
messaging systems like PSST, X-IM and CryptIM, eavesdropping methods=20
like the FBI's Carnivore system (also called DCS1000) become less=20
useful. Both Free World Dialup's Pulver, and Niklas Zennstrom, founder=20=

of Skype, said last month that their services currently offer no easy=20
wiretap route for police because VoIP calls travel along the Internet=20
in tens of thousands of packets, each sometimes taking completely=20
different routes.

Skype has become a hot-button in the debate by automatically encrypting=20=

all calls that take place through the peer-to-peer voice application.

The origins of this debate date back to when the FBI persuaded Congress=20=

to enact the controversial CALEA. Louis Freeh, FBI director at the=20
time, testified in 1994 that emerging technologies such as call=20
forwarding, call waiting and cellular phones had frustrated=20
surveillance efforts.

Congress responded to the FBI's concern by requiring that=20
telecommunications services rewire their networks to provide police=20
with guaranteed access for wiretaps. Legislators also granted the FCC=20
substantial leeway in defining what types of companies must comply. So=20=

far, the FCC has interpreted CALEA's wiretap-ready requirements to=20
cover only traditional analog and wireless telephone service,=A0 leaving=20=

broadband and Internet applications in a regulatory gray area.

Under the FBI's proposal, Internet companies would bear "sole financial=20=

responsibility for development and implementation of CALEA solutions"=20
but would be authorized to raise prices to cover their costs.=20=

--Apple-Mail-2-189505112--

Subject: [sfraves] (NRR) FBI pushes for broadband wiretap powers

FBI pushes for broadband wiretap powers
ISPs, Net phone services would all have to rewire
By Ben Charny
March 12, 2004

A far-reaching proposal from the FBI, made public Friday, would require=20
all broadband Internet providers, including cable modem and DSL=20
companies, to rewire their networks to support easy wiretapping by=20
police.

The FBI's request to the Federal Communications Commission aims to give=20
police ready access to any form of Internet-based communications. If=20
approved as drafted, the proposal could dramatically expand the scope=20
of the agency's wiretap powers, raise costs for cable broadband=20
companies and complicate Internet product development.

Legal experts said the 85-page filing includes language that could be=20
interpreted as forcing companies to build backdoors into everything=20
from instant messaging and voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) programs=20
to Microsoft's Xbox Live gaming service. The introduction of new=20
services that did not support a back door for police would be outlawed,=20
and companies would be given 15 months to make sure existing services=20
comply.

"The importance and the urgency of this task cannot be overstated,"=20
says the proposal, which is also backed by the U.S. Department of=20
Justice and the Drug Enforcement Administration.

"The ability of federal, state and local law enforcement to carry out=20
critical electronic surveillance is being compromised today."

Because the eavesdropping scheme has the support of the Bush=20
administration, the FCC is expected to take it very seriously. Last=20
month, FCC Chairman Michael Powell stressed that "law enforcement=20
access to IP-enabled communications is essential" and police must have=20
"access to communications infrastructure they need to protect our=20
nation."

The request from federal police comes almost a year after=20
representatives from the FBI's Electronic Surveillance Technology=20
Section approached the FCC and asked that broadband providers be=20
required to provide more efficient, standardized surveillance=20
facilities. Such new rules were necessary, the FBI argued, because=20
terrorists could otherwise frustrate legitimate wiretaps by placing=20
phone calls over the Internet.

"It is a very big deal and will be very costly for the Internet and the=20
deployment of new technologies," said Stewart Baker, who represents=20
Internet providers as a partner at the Steptoe and Johnson law firm.=20
"Law enforcement is very serious about it. There is a lot of emotion=20
behind this. They have stories that they're very convinced about in=20
which they have not achieved access to communications and in which=20
wiretaps have failed."

Broadband in the mix
Broadband providers say the FBI's request would, for the first time,=20
force cable providers that sell broadband to come under the=20
jurisdiction of 1994's Communications Assistance for Law Enforcement=20
Act (CALEA), which further defined the already existing statutory=20
obligations of telecommunications carriers to help police conduct=20
electronic surveillance. Telephone companies that use their networks to=20
sell broadband have already been following CALEA rules.

"For cable companies, it's all new," said Bellsouth spokesman Bill=20
McCloskey.

Several cable providers, including Comcast Communications, Time Warner=20
Cable and Cablevision had no immediate comment on the FBI's request.

The FBI proposal would also force Vonage, 8x8, AT&T and other prominent=20
providers of broadband telephone services to comply with CALEA.=20
Executives from these companies have said in the past that they all=20
intend to comply with any request law enforcement makes, if technically=20
possible.

Broadband phone service providers say they are already creating a code=20
of conduct to cover some of the same issues addressed by the FBI, but=20
on a voluntary basis, according to Jeff Pulver, founder of Free World=20
Dialup.

"We have our chance right now to prove to law enforcement that we can=20
do this on a voluntary basis," Pulver said. "If we mandate and make=20
rules, it will just complicate things."

Under CALEA, police must still follow legal procedures when wiretapping=20
Internet communications. Depending on the situation, such wiretaps do=20
not always require court approval, in part because of changes to=20
wiretapping laws made by the USA Patriot Act.

A Verizon representative said Friday that the company has already=20
complied with at least one law enforcement request to tap a DSL line.

This week's proposal surprised privacy advocates by reaching beyond=20
broadband providers to target companies that offer communications=20
applications such as instant messaging clients.

"I don't think it's a reasonable claim," said Marc Rotenberg, director=20
of the Electronic Privacy Information Center. "The FCC should seriously=20
consider where the FBI believes its authority ... to regulate new=20
technologies would end. What about Bluetooth and USB?"

Baker agrees that the FBI's proposal means that IP-based services such=20
as chat programs and videoconferencing "that are 'switched' in any=20
fashion would be treated as telephony."

If the FCC agrees, Baker said, "you would have to vet your designs with=20
law enforcement before providing your service. There will be a queue.=20
There will be politics involved. It would completely change the way=20
services are introduced on the Internet."

As encryption becomes glued into more and more VoIP and instant=20
messaging systems like PSST, X-IM and CryptIM, eavesdropping methods=20
like the FBI's Carnivore system (also called DCS1000) become less=20
useful. Both Free World Dialup's Pulver, and Niklas Zennstrom, founder=20
of Skype, said last month that their services currently offer no easy=20
wiretap route for police because VoIP calls travel along the Internet=20
in tens of thousands of packets, each sometimes taking completely=20
different routes.

Skype has become a hot-button in the debate by automatically encrypting=20
all calls that take place through the peer-to-peer voice application.

The origins of this debate date back to when the FBI persuaded Congress=20
to enact the controversial CALEA. Louis Freeh, FBI director at the=20
time, testified in 1994 that emerging technologies such as call=20
forwarding, call waiting and cellular phones had frustrated=20
surveillance efforts.

Congress responded to the FBI's concern by requiring that=20
telecommunications services rewire their networks to provide police=20
with guaranteed access for wiretaps. Legislators also granted the FCC=20
substantial leeway in defining what types of companies must comply. So=20
far, the FCC has interpreted CALEA's wiretap-ready requirements to=20
cover only traditional analog and wireless telephone service,=A0 leaving =

broadband and Internet applications in a regulatory gray area.

Under the FBI's proposal, Internet companies would bear "sole financial=20
responsibility for development and implementation of CALEA solutions"=20
but would be authorized to raise prices to cover their costs.=20
