SATURDAY, March 20th
(The Spring Equinox)

10PM to 6:30 AM

In celebration of twenty years of house music
and two years of MOKSHA TRIBE parties
we are proud to bring you...

**CATCH 20-2**

"In the beginning there was Jack, and Jack had a groove..."

With special guest JESSE SAUNDERS!!! Using a blueprint of old school funk, 
disco, R&B, early pop and hip-hop, JESSE SAUNDERS is the architect of the 
musical style known as "House Music."  He wrote, produced and released the 
first documented House record titled "ON & ON" through his own label Jes 
Say Records.

And ADAM OHANA.  Adam Ohana has been DJing and producing electronic music 
for over 10 years under various monikers and has been an instrumental part 
of the underground music culture in SF.  Adam has recently been focusing 
his musical energies and talents on  breaks music as a medium to express 
his love for different styles.  Ohana has a variety of breaks releases 
scheduled under the name an.ten.nae, and is the force behind the amazing 
"Get Freaky" parties

parties.

Subject: [sfraves] NRR:  Oppose internet wiretapping

--=====================_3560489==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

Not satisfied with the new snooping powers granted by the PATRIOT Act, the 
Department of Justice is now asking the Federal Communications Commission 
to allow law enforcement the power to regulate the design of Internet 
communications services to make them easy to wiretap.

If implemented, the new request by Attorney General John Ashcroft would 
dramatically increase the government's surveillance powers and set a 
precedent for opening the entire Internet to law enforcement. By forcing 
technology companies to build "backdoors" in their systems for wiretapping, 
the Ashcroft plan would also create weaknesses that hackers and thieves 
could use to invade your privacy and steal personal information like credit 
card numbers.

The government already has more than enough power to spy on individuals 
suspected of wrongdoing. This measure is the equivalent of requiring all 
new homes be built with a peephole for law enforcement agents to look through.

Take Action!  Tell the FCC and Congress that you oppose these new 
wiretapping requirements.

Click here for more information and to send a free fax to the FCC Chairman 
and your Members of Congress:

http://www.aclu.org/Privacy/Privacy.cfm?ID=15264&c=39

MIME-Version: 1.0

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] BSP: One Man's Trash is Another's Gold


BAD TRIUMPH!!!

DO NOT SELL SECOND COPIES OF STUFF!

On Thu, 18 Mar 2004, Jack Triumph wrote:
-&e->Hey, being the genius I am, not, I accidentally ordered 2 copies of
-&e->

Your assignment, go home and rock your doubles.

Here's your list of doubles tricks:

1.	The Flange(easy)
	Set up both your decks to 0 pitch lock.  Set the crossfader in the
middle.  Cue both records up.  Let em fly at the same time.  Now slowly
wobble the flange back and forth with the pitch knob on one side.  Yay,
it's like flanging.  Actually, it is flanging.  Long before flange was a
button on your Pioneer or a guitar pedal you stomped on, tacky 60s
producers got this effect by playing identical copies of a tape and
pressing their thumbs on the flange of the reels (the outside edge)...
giving the sound it's name.

2.	The stutterer(medium)
	Cue both records as above in the Flange.  Throw one half a beat
after the other.  Now you should have a 4/4 beat playing double time (same
sound you'd get through a delay set to an 1/8th note delay).  Now go
apeshit with crossfader.  For double kick fun, you can cut the mids and
his on one copy.  Get creative, this one never runs out of ideas.  You can
even create breakbeats from 4/4 and vice versa doing this and some well
timed crossfader thrashing.

3.	The juggle(easy-hard depending on how short your phrase is)
	Set up records as before, but play just one.  Then on the 16th
beat, throw the other copy and cut the crossfader to it.  Now cue the
first one back to the beginning.  As your skill increases consider marking
your records (this is easier to do visually than by listening when you get
to less than 8 beats of looping).

4.	Sampledrop (medium)
	Got a sound you like in the record about halfway through?  Play
the first record normally, then cue up the sample you'd like to scratch or
drop in on the other record.  Now, as the sound comes up on the first
record, you can create a buildup using the other copy and the
crossfader/level fader, or 'echo' the sound by letting the first record
play it, then doing a simple cut and volume fade out (scratching echo
effect).

5.	Hello DuctTape (hard)
	Find the little chrome weight that came with your 1200.
	Find a mostly used spool of duct tape.
	Place the spool of ducttape on your slipmat.  And center it.
	Now take your cartridge and take it off.  Turn it over and put it
back on.  You should have a needle pointing up into the air.
	Now pull the weight on the tonearm all the way back (away from the
fulcrum).  Add the little chrome jobby on the end.
	Now place the tonearm in it's rest and snap it in there (it will
tend to act all crazy cause it's backweighted now).
	Now carefully center your record atop the ducttape.
	You can now play the bottom side of the record.  It will track
backwards.  How fucking cool is that?  Only minus is rarely are tracks
designed to be cued from the back (and the little fingerlift part of most
carts prevents from doing this anyway cause it runs into the duct tape
spool).
	Once you've got this going, you can use the speed adjust and
gentle pressure down at the center of the record to beatmatch a copy of
the record going backwards with the other copy going forwards.  Plus this
looks really neato anyway.  Ok, so I've done this one all of twice in
front of people... but conceptually it's dope as all hell.

6.	Halfstops (hard)
	Take two copies and set up em like you did with the flange.  Now
you can leave the cross fader in the middle and let one beat go from one
record and stop it.  Now let one beat go from the other record.  Once
you've got a good solid 'boom *eenr* boom *eenr* boom *eenr* boom' at
about half the speed of the original recording, learn to throw the
crossfader between steps to mask the part where you hear the record slow
down.  Also, for a more interesting sound, play with the offset (starting
both records at the 1 sounds sorta silly and not so slick but it's the
best way to learn the physical/muscle memory part of it).

7.	Timed drops (exercise)
	Practice letting one copy play, and then cueing the other one to a
point further in the record and cue it in right at the point where the
first record plays it (bringing in a flange at that point).  Once you've
got that, learn to set the crossfader centered and stop one record for
four beats and throw it back in.  Alternate sides so you learn well timed
cueing with either hand.

8.	Effects done right (easy)
	Throw in a manner similar to the flange, but set one channel up
for effects and one not.  Now you can switch effects in and out by mashing
the crossfader back and forth.  No click!  No pop!  Yay!!!  Now hear the
DJ get wicked with running a timed delay on one side, and then stopping
the record with the delay right before a big change in the tune and hit
the stop button.  Oh yay!

These tricks serve several purposes.  One is that in the right context
they blow people's heads off if you land them correctly.  Also, they put
more of a turntablist type regimen into your DJing practice, keeping it
more interesting than just the beatmatch & count bullshit most people do.
You learn confidence when cueing and throwing, you learn how to cue a
record quickly without skipping the groove.  With two copies, you are no
longer tied to the linear progression of the tune... you can cut out the
break or play it twice.  You get a lot of say in what happens that you
wouldn't have without those skills.  You fight the perception that all
dance music DJs can do is smoothmix.  And when you die, you will be
honored as ninja/samurai and drink much mead.

or not.
andyw

a trueschool community reunion of art, techno and electro under one roof

B-boys & B-girls welcome. Downrock at your own risk. 


Robot Feelings will be located at Cellspace in San Francisco.  Cellspace is a 
drug and alcohol free community arts venue. Respect the space and surrounding 
neighborhood. Do not flyer cars surrounding the space. No markers, 
paint/tips, scribers, etc. allowed inside the venue.  No ins and outs are allowed after 
10pm.  A smoking area will be provided. Please respect the rules of the venue 
so that others may congregate there in the future.

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Leaving for now.

Tis a sad day for this list, or not, since I have not posted in, oh, well, 
at least a year or so! To be blunt, I simply have no time anymore, I have 
not had time to paruse the list since I got married! Alot has changed, I 
will be turning 31 next week, and I am moving into a house that I now own in 
Oakland. Kinda wierd, a raver home-owner? I know there are some of us on 
this list out there, who ever you are, isn't that the next stage of life 
after buying a washer and dryer? Well I am told that my taxes will decrease 
whilst my property taxes will, well, make up for the loss. But at least I am 
now investing in the future instead of someone elses future by renting!

But I digress, in case you are still wondering, yes I am still spinning the 
good shit, but now I am closer to the FNF crowd than I am the SFR group. 
Guess it is a natural progression as one gets older, I simply have more 
contacts in the FNF community now, since my realestate agent is an FNFer and 
my mortgage broker is Greg Sandler! Yep, you are reading me right, Greg is 
in the realestate market now, and he is a damn good dood for the job. Who 
would have guessed? I actually met him in his new position at the SFR 
outdoor several years ago and he has been a really good friend ever since.

So, without further adew, I bid you a fond fairwell, we have had many good 
times together, both good and bad. I will remember the few that I used to 
spar with on this list, and the rest with passing fancy and a smile. I got 
as much out of this list as I put into it, I can only hope that the world 
was a better place for it, during the good times and bad. All I have left to 
say is "So long and thanks for all the fish". See ya when I see ya, but 
never goodbye forever.

           Alex Van Dune

I am reminded of the immortal words of Socrates who once said
     "I drank what?"

PS: For replys please email me at alexvanduyn@sbcglobal.net for further 
correspondence.

i have a very good family doctor who just so happens to be the same =
doctor i had in my PPO before
kaiser bought the facility out, however he is in alameda, not sf.

i also had a new hot-shot surgeon at kaiser re-attach the knee-joint end =
of my femur after i broke
it in a way that i would wish on my worst enemy (at FnF '02.)

on the other hand, others have had legitimately horrible experiences =
with kaiser.

it is a HUGE organization.  there will be good doctors and bad =
doctors... hence the reason he is
asking.

so stfu =3D)

idiotic that "reasoning" is.

does that have anything to do with being wary of all people who own guns ?  where is the connection
?  oh, that's right... there IS no connection between the person who killed my friend and all people
who own guns, nor is there any plausible connection between the doctor that may have caused harm to
the afformentioned mother and ALL kaizer doctors.

and with that, Kaiser in Alameda, Dr. Harrington is a down-to-earth old-skool mofo who doesn't treat
you like you don't know shit about your own body.

peeeesh ! (out)

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: looking for a good kaiser doctor

I don't think the issue is whether kaiser has good drs or not........I'm
sure theres at least a couple.  The issue is  kaiser's way of doing business
with and treating their patients.  They don't order anything you don't
absolutely need at the moment.  So a lot of shit that does get checked other
places goes unoticed at kaiser.  If you aren't going to die, you don't need
it.  thats been my and many other people's experience.......I work in the
medical field and have heard some ungodly stories, and personal experiences
from co-wrokers and patients.

Most HMO's aren't much better......its sad

Molly

Subject: RE: [sfraves] NRR: looking for a good kaiser doctor

Yeah, although there always has to be some way to limit costs. The idea of
"unlimited free universal healthcare" is an illusion, there's no way any
society can afford it. Kaiser seems to be OK as long as there's not
anything seriously wrong with you. When there is, you have to advocate
extremely forcefully for yourself, and even then the care you'll get
usually won't be great. For primary care it should be possible to find
someone good. Someone help the guy out.

and

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: looking for a good kaiser doctor

	Health care costs in countries with socialist medicine *aren't* =20=

limited, just disguised. I think that's what Dan was saying. If you =20
don't pay for your own health care up front, someone else will be =20
paying. If the medical providers aren't reimbursed for those costs, =20
then they have to charge other people more for their health care to =20
make up for it.

	Also, when the patient pays nothing, then the patient has no =
incentive =20
to keep costs down. He or she will seek the best treatment available, =20=

rather than the most cost-effective treatment. To give an example, say =20=

you can either take an HIV test that determines with 99% accuracy =20
whether you have HIV, and this test costs $20. Or you can take a test =20=

that will determine whether you have HIV with 99.9% accuracy, but this =20=

test costs $1000. If you're paying for the test, you'd probably choose =20=

the $20 test. But if Kaiser's paying, or the government's paying, or =20
someone else is paying, then you'll naturally take the more accurate =20
test. There's no downside for you.

	If the doctor doesn't pay anything extra for the $1000 test, and =
=20
there's no insurance company involved either, then *no one* has an =20
incentive to economize. This lack of connection between who pays and =20
who is involved in the decision is one of the reasons that health care =20=

costs have gone through the roof.

Peace, love & liberty,
					<<< Starchild >>>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: looking for a good kaiser doctor

	Pharmaceutical companies deserve little of the blame for rising health 
care costs. In order to legally be able to sell a new drug in the 
United States, they face a horrendous government approval process. It 
now takes about 15 years and costs about $897 million to introduce 
*each new drug*. To stay in business, companies have to pass these 
development costs along to the people who buy the drugs. That's why 
prescription drugs are outrageously expensive. From 
http://www.techcentralstation.com/060903B.html:

"In fact, the total time required for drug development, from synthesis 
of the molecule to marketing approval, has more than doubled (from 6.5 
to about 15 years) since 1964. In spite of more powerful and precise 
technologies for drug discovery, purification and production, 
development costs have skyrocketed. According to the Tufts Center for 
the Study of Drug Development, between 1970 and 2003 companies' average 
expenditures to develop a single new drug exploded, increasing from 
$138 million to $897 million. And while between 1970 and 2000, 
research-based companies' R&D outlays soared from about $2 billion to 
$30 billion, the number of approvals of new drugs barely budged. An 
important reason is that the highly risk-averse FDA keeps raising the 
bar for approval, especially for innovative, high-tech products.

"The FDA contends that it's getting better and moving drugs through the 
pipeline more rapidly - thanks, they say, to user fees paid by drug 
companies (in effect, a huge, discriminatory tax) - but the data tell a 
different story. Although the time FDA takes to grant the final 
approval for marketing a biopharmaceutical has not changed appreciably 
during the past 20 years, the time required to meet the FDA's 
requirements for gathering clinical trials data has more than doubled: 
32 months during the 1980s, 48 months during 1990-94, 64 months during 
1995-99, and 72 months during 2000-02.

"The trend in cancer drug approvals is illustrative. Vanderbilt 
University researchers who study the development and approvals of 
cancer drugs have concluded that projected out over the period from 
2000-2004, we can expect to see a 68 percent reduction in new drug 
approvals and a 37 percent reduction in the number of claims approved 
for new cancer indications (uses), compared to the preceding five-year 
period (1995-1999)..."

	One of the most important things that could be done to make health 
care affordable in this country would be to get rid of the FDA. Since 
the agency has cost many more lives than it has saved (by preventing 
people from using life-saving drugs as soon as possible), returning to 
taxpayers the millions of dollars wasted on it every year would be 
humane as well as practical.

First do no harm,
					<<< Starchild >>>

SATURDAY, March 20th
(The Spring Equinox)

10PM to 6:30 AM

In celebration of twenty years of house music
and two years of MOKSHA TRIBE parties
we are proud to bring you...

**CATCH 20-2**

"In the beginning there was Jack, and Jack had a groove..."

With special guest JESSE SAUNDERS!!! Using a blueprint of old school funk, =
disco, R&B, early pop and hip-hop, JESSE SAUNDERS is the architect of the m=
usical style known as "House Music."  He wrote, produced and released the f=
irst documented House record titled "ON & ON" through his own label Jes Say=
 Records.

And ADAM OHANA.  Adam Ohana has been DJing and producing electronic music f=
or over 10 years under various monikers and has been an instrumental part o=
f the underground music culture in SF.  Adam has recently been focusing his=
 musical energies and talents on  breaks music as a medium to express his l=
ove for different styles.  Ohana has a variety of breaks releases scheduled=
 under the name an.ten.nae, and is the force behind the amazing "Get Freaky=
" parties

  *************PLEASE DO NOT POST TO OTHER LISTS***************


SATURDAY, March 20th
(The Spring Equinox)

10PM to 6:30 AM

In celebration of twenty years of house music
and two years of MOKSHA TRIBE parties
we are proud to bring you...

**CATCH 20-2**

"In the beginning there was Jack, and Jack had a groove..."

With special guest JESSE SAUNDERS!!! Using a blueprint of old school funk, 
disco, R&B, early pop and hip-hop, JESSE SAUNDERS is the architect of the 
musical style known as "House Music."  He wrote, produced and released the 
first documented House record titled "ON & ON" through his own label Jes 
Say Records.

And ADAM OHANA.  Adam Ohana has been DJing and producing electronic music 
for over 10 years under various monikers and has been an instrumental part 
of the underground music culture in SF.  Adam has recently been focusing 
his musical energies and talents on  breaks music as a medium to express 
his love for different styles.  Ohana has a variety of breaks releases 
scheduled under the name an.ten.nae, and is the force behind the amazing 
"Get Freaky" parties


Four full rooms of music with decorations and themes from past Moksha Tribe 
parties.
Come dressed as you did at your favorite Moksha event.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The Aboriginal Room:
House and Tech House
(in order of appearance)

Apollo  (Paradise Garage, founder of Moksha Tribe)
Origami  (Moksha Tribe, newstylesound)
Jesse Saunders (originator of house music, King Street/Broken Records, Sony 
Music)
DJ Amber (:CODE, SisterSF, Justsayagency)
DilemaFunk Doc (Moksha Tribe)

The Jagan Room:
Breaks, Tech House, Psytrance, Industrial

ShezTek (Moksha Tribe, Ambreaks, Evolving Spectrum Productions)
Adam Ohana (an-ten-nae, Get Freaky)
Shazbot (Moksha Tribe, newstylesound)
nomadic DJ (Moksha Tribe)
Marshal (Moksha Tribe, SWAT Sound)

The Deviance Room:
Breaks, Ghetto tech, Hip hop,
Ragga Jungle Dub Plate Business, Drum 'n' bass

Jauncy (Moksha Tribe)
Andy W (Resourcerecords, Refined Music, Viberation) with MC Boomerang 
Fidget (Ambient Mafia)
Koda (Urban Drums, Basedonbass.com, Owned Clothing)
The Doctor (BayRaves, Liquid Vinyl DJs)
Marcine (Moksha Tribe)

The Harvest Room:
Ambient beats, chill room

DV8 (Moksha Tribe, Evolving Spectrum Productions)
Red Stickman (Moksha Tribe, Ambient Mafia)
Calamity Jane (Moksha Tribe, Ambreaks)
V0lljude (Dub Beautiful Collective)
Brian Behlendorf (founder, sfraves)

Visuals by Viberation
Sound by SWAT

Convenient Bay Area underground location
18+

As always, you will be treated with love and respect and offered:

*Free Water
*Free fruit
*Free refreshments
*Free toys

Massages by Ravin' Riz to benefit Larkin Street
Smoothies by Philip Diaz

ALL PROFITS FROM THIS EVENT WILL BE DONATED TO LARKIN STREET YOUTH SERVICES

<http://www.larkinstreetyouth.org/>www.larkinstreetyouth.org


Limited presale tickets are available through PayPal for $13.00 to cover 
transaction costs
until 7:00 PM tonight.
   Check our Catch 20-2 website to purchase via PayPal:

www.mokshatribe.org/catch22/

PayPal purchased tickets will be held at will call (PayPal receipt and ID 
required).

Tickets for this special event are selling rapidly.  To assure admission we 
suggest you
purchase your tickets before 7:00 PM through either PayPal or Moksha 
members.  If there are
  tickets remaining tonight they will be sold first-come-first-served at 
the door for $14.00, with $2.00 going
directly to Larkin Street.  Please check the info line for updates.

INFO LINE:  415-564-4768

Call the info line tonight for directions to the venue and ticket availability.




Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org
                 www.mokshatribe.org/catch22/

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Security is mostly a superstition.  It does not exist in nature, nor do 
the children of humans as a whole experience it.  Avoiding danger is no 
safer in the long run than outright exposure.  Life is either a daring 
adventure or nothing."
-Helen Keller

The dangerous patriot: "The one who drifts into chauvinism and exhibits 
blind enthusiasm for military actions. He is a defender of militarism and 
its ideals of war and glory. Chauvinism is a proud and bellicose form of 
patriotism . . . which identifies numerous enemies who can only be dealt 
with through military power and which equates the national honor with 
military victory..."
-Marine Corps, Colonel James A. Donovan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Sup party peoples?

Tomorrow night on the show we've got an ill show for ya, with John Tab,
Locks, and Crucial Carl bringin you the flavors that drum 'n' bass, as we
know it, has come from.  I'm still workin out the timeslots and such, and
I'll update them on the site when I know for sure.  To tune in to the
shizzle follow ze links below:

128k audio: http://64.246.60.15:8800/listen.pls
64k audio: http://jungletrain.net/64kbps.pls
24k audio: http://jungletrain.net/24kbps.pls

chatttt: http://jungletrain.net/index.php?page=2&subpage=0&color=2

AIM: dirtboxradio

links below for ya.  They'll be up for another month or so, so grab 'em
while they is hawt!

The Moksha crew all had much fun too last night -- seeing so many of you 
rocking on the dance floor, including Andy W:)  Jesse was really on last 
night.  I haven't seen him personally have so much fun performing at a 
party since the Chicago days.  We had to pry him away from the decks, and I 
think if we let him he would have gone on for the rest of the evening.  He 
stayed and talked in the crew room until around 5:30.

I'll write an "official" thank you from the Moksha Tribe tomorrow.  Man, 
exhausted today and we still have to do some more strike tonight but 
there's no better work, to my mind, than throwing a party like we all did 
-- both the crew and you lovely guests -- last night.

Much love,

Apollo

On Mon, 22 Mar 2004 DJBigDaddyG@aol.com wrote:
-&e->http://cgi.ebay.com/ws/eBayISAPI.dll?ViewItem&item=4002909629&category=306
-&e->
-&e->HERE ARE THE TRACKS AND TITLES & LABEL , style!!!!!
-&e->
-&e->1. TALKING HEADS-FEAR OF MUSIC FULL LP-ORIGINAL COVER & 12" SLIP-RECORD IN
-&e->MINT CONDITION-COVER A LITTLE WORN-1979 SIRE RECORDS

There's one tune on there that *is* kinda housey (and someone did a remix
of it just a couple years ago).

-&e->2. SIMPLE MINDS-SISTER FEELINGS CAL-FULL LP-COVER AND RECORD IN MINT
-&e->SHAP-VIRGIN RECORDS 1987

Weak album.

-&e->3. SIMPLE MINDS-STREET FIGHTING YEARS-FULL LP IN MINT SHAP-BRAND NEW
-&e->CONDITION-1989 VIRGIN RECORDS
-&e->4. THE SMITHS-RARE 3 TRACK PROMO ON ROUGH TRADE RECORDS 1986-ORIGINAL
-&e->PRINTING IN MINT SHAPE CLASSIC -

Kinda cool.  But not dance music either.

-&e->5. CULTURE CLUB-COLOUR BY NUMBERS-RARE BOY GEORGE ORIGINAL PRESSING OF THIS
-&e->CLASSIC LP-1983 ORIGINAL COVER AND SLIP-INCLUDES SONGS: KARMA CHAMELEON-THAT'S
-&e->TEH WAY

Rare my ass.  This record sold millions in original copy.

-&e->6. MADONA-ANGEL-ORIGINAL 1985 PRESSING ON SIRE RECORDS-IN MINT SHAPE-EXT
-&e->DANCE MIX AND INTO THE GROOVE ORIGINAL
-&e->7. 8. DAO DEZI-TI ELIZ IZA-RARE JORIO REMIXES BEFORE HE GOT HUGE AND DID
-&e->STUFF WITH OAKENFOLD AND DANNY TENAGLIA-1995 NEW
-&e->9. KLEO-TELL ME -RARE PROMO FOR DJ ONLY-200 MADE-THIS WAS A CLASSIC CLUB
-&e->TRACK PLAYED BY TENAGLIA AND MANY OTHERS
-&e->10. CHUMBAWAMBA-TUBTHUMPING-CLASSIC LATE 90'S DANCE AND CLUB TRACK-RARE
-&e->ORIGINAL WHITE LABEL PROMO 1997 ON REPUBLIC RECORDS5 MIXES TOTAL NEW NEVER PLAYED

This isn't really trance or house... it's more like someone getting rid of
a bunch of stuff that's not rare and just hyping it up a bit.

This is the shiz right here:
http://cgi.ebay.com/ws/eBayISAPI.dll?ViewItem&item=4003130384&category=306

Anybody that's from LA and packing double copies of C+C "gonna make you
sweat"  is like totally psycho or a wedding DJ from Compton that just got
chipped out of an iceblock that froze over in 1992 (holy crap, got doubles
of Tone Loc too...).  Actually damn... *andy shakes paypal account upside
down and nothing comes out*.  And Marrs... hahahaha...

Or here, this is actually kinda cool (100 pieces of probably decent
techno at about $2 a piece shipped):
http://cgi.ebay.com/ws/eBayISAPI.dll?ViewItem&item=4002426401&category=306

But that said... the cheapest way to find your voice as a DJ is to go to
record stores or online sites where you can listen before you buy.  That
way you only buy what you enjoy, and that's a great foundation for
expressing yourself.  There are some used record stores that are like
goldmines that you'll never find all the gold in letting stuff go at a
few bucks a pop.

Let the music take control, let the rhythm move you.
andyw

music) record companies (sorry I'm not going to tell which ones, but =
lets just say one of them is from the UK and one of them is from the US) =
telling me that they liked my demo and want more material.
=20
I happily spent the rest of the day in the studio trying to bang out new =
material.
=20
Anyone know any good web-designers/graphic artists? I need to get a =
web-site, but I want it to look pro. Will offer fair pay for quality =
work.
=20
Steve OSTEEN
Progressive DJ/Producer
=20

Subject: [sfraves] CATCH 20-2:  Our Deepest Appreciation!!!!

--=====================_2493335==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

Moksha Tribe sends our deepest appreciation to all of you who came out on 
Saturday night for Catch 20-2.  This was a very special event for Moksha -- 
our second anniversary and the twentieth birthday of house music -- and all 
of you who shared this evening with us represented the very best qualities 
of the raver community.  The vibe was excellent and lord knows all of the 
DJs were right on.  Jesse Saunders did one of the best sets I've heard him 
deliver in awhile to a very appreciative audience, as did our other 
performers.  And all of you danced and danced throughout the night.  Makes 
my heart sing:)

I can tell you now that your participation (we sold out) and generous 
donations raised lots of money for the homeless kids in the Bay Area.  When 
we finish the accounting I'll let you know how we did.

The only blight on an otherwise stellar evening was the arrival of local 
law enforcement around 4 AM.  Two immature, aggressive, macho officers were 
denied entrance to the party, but forced their way in over our objections 
to deliver a rather ambiguous mandate to the dancers in the Jagan room, 
causing much discomfort and confusion.  I believe they were well out of 
their legal structure to do so.  We were a private party in a private 
venue.  I can tell you this:  we have never ended a party so far because of 
police action.  In our usual tradition we assessed the situation, made some 
changes in the sound configuration, and continued on until 6:30 AM as 
planned.  We still had guests relaxing at the site until around eight.  I 
personally was saddened by this because many of you missed some good music 
feeling you had to leave.  Amber and Nomadic DJ did a tag team set in the 
Jagan room that really rocked, and Brian Behlendorf's closing ambient set 
in the chill room was awesomely beautiful.

Such potential drama, of course, comes with the territory but none of this 
diminishes our passion to provide safe, memorable evenings of music and 
dance -- yes, raves -- to our extended family:  you, our friends and 
supporters.

Again, thanks to all of you for your good vibes and love.  We are looking 
forward to providing you with many more evenings of love and light in future.

Much love,

Apollo for Moksha Tribe


Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Security is mostly a superstition.  It does not exist in nature, nor do 
the children of humans as a whole experience it.  Avoiding danger is no 
safer in the long run than outright exposure.  Life is either a daring 
adventure or nothing."
-Helen Keller

The dangerous patriot: "The one who drifts into chauvinism and exhibits 
blind enthusiasm for military actions. He is a defender of militarism and 
its ideals of war and glory. Chauvinism is a proud and bellicose form of 
patriotism . . . which identifies numerous enemies who can only be dealt 
with through military power and which equates the national honor with 
military victory..."
-Marine Corps, Colonel James A. Donovan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"  
--=====================_2493335==.ALT--

Subject: [sfraves] (Review) Equinox, Moksha, Sunset

I didn't think it was possible, but I am partied out. I went to the 
Equinox party on Friday and got to spin fire with my friends. There was 
so much energy in the air as the dawn of the first day of spring was 
approaching. The Moksha party. There aren't words to describe this 
glorious night. I loved the layout of this party, much better than 
Jagen, which was in the same space. The warm, inviting, family vibe that 
I have come to expect from Moksha  was plentiful, and despite the cowboy 
cops with something to prove, the fun lasted until after sunup. It was 
great to see so many people I haven't seen in a while, as well as to 
meet lots of new folks. Oh, and I got to spin fire again. Sunday I slept 
till 2:00, then made my way to my first Sunset party. I was pretty burnt 
out, but I enjoyed sitting in my big canvas chair listening to the 
music, and being entertained by all the lively people around me. And...I 
got to spin fire again. Yeah, I'm addicted. Thanks for the big hugs and 
positive energy that I got from everyone I saw this weekend. Time to 
rest up, so we can do it again next weekend!

Happy

Catch 20-2 was amazing! It was my first Moksha Tribe party -- although Osby 
has been telling me to go since Day 1 -- and I was so impressed. Wonderful 
vibe, beautififul & creative decorations, many friendly people, and, of course, 
really bangin' music. Apollo and the other Moksha Tribe members are to be 
commended for throwing such a fantastic event. Jesse Saunders played with so much 
energy. All the DJs were great! (I'd never seen a DJ play the electric bass 
while spinning -- that was ultra cool!)

I've got my pics posted on www.deciblast.org

-------------------------------1080005369--

I thought this would be a good time to mention a
couple things I've noticed.

Specifically with this party, and another one last
weekend at a certian lofty location in SF...

Both of these venues were set up as (IMO) nothing less
than deathtraps.
(The loft literally had the windows sealed shit with
plywood- can't get to a fire-escape through a
boarded-off window)

I've been to that meaty-supreme location probably
about  10 times now, and am very familiar with it's
flexibility in setup.
I don't know who (Moksha/venue-owners/whatever) was
responsible for the literally-one-person-wide hallway
that you had to go through to get in, but that was
just *totally* irresponsible.
Had a fire started in any of the back areas, you would
have had many hundreds of asphyxiated people on your
hands...
Please correct me if I'm wrong, but I didn't notice
any fire extinguishers anywhere either...

Running that much sound on a dubious aging electrical
system, with no (seen) fire extinguishers, while
blocking almost every exit out of the place with a
single-person-wide corridor?
...
Fire codes are there for a reason, and I know this is
the underground but please- that was *ridiculous*-

Well, Nathan, you're wrong on that point.  We always place fire 
extinguishers behind the DJ booths in every room.  The collective owns 
quite a few.  Further, the crew is has very specific instructions for 
safety in fire situations.  Although it may appear that you were all 
boarded in, there are quite a few fire exits in that location that would be 
revealed in an emergence by sliding open several steel doors.  Further, the 
fire marshal has inspected and certified the venue.

Safety, Nathan, is also our concern.

Love,

Apollo

the children of humans as a whole experience it.  Avoiding danger is no 
safer in the long run than outright exposure.  Life is either a daring 
adventure or nothing."
-Helen Keller

blind enthusiasm for military actions. He is a defender of militarism and 
its ideals of war and glory. Chauvinism is a proud and bellicose form of 
patriotism . . . which identifies numerous enemies who can only be dealt 
with through military power and which equates the national honor with 
military victory..."
-Marine Corps, Colonel James A. Donovan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

SOMA Sessions

THIS FRIDAY March 26, 2004

ASC (Covert Operations, ASCaudio.com - UK)
A prolific producer and head of the Covert Operations
label, ASC has signed tunes to 720, Good Looking,
Offshore and Nu Directions to name a few. He and his
stable of cutting-edge artists from around the globe
have outgrown the Atmospheric D&B moniker as they turn
their focus toward maximum dancefloor impact.

ILLFORMANTS (Breakbeat Science, Subtitles)
Recording separately as Controlled Substance and Angel
Zero, this duo have turned heads in recent years with
stormers such as The Bizarre. Their fresh take on
techstep is characterized by crisp beats and sci-fi
sound effects rolling out over deep deadly basslines.
Expect another storming B2B set from these Bay Area
favorites!

Resident Support:
SOUND:BOY (SOMA Sessions, Hemisphere, Brass Tax)
DJ M (SOMA Sessions, Faultline, Freebeats)

available now from Cov.Ops & Warm Communications:

Probe-One, Tidal and more.  Shipping now at
http://www.techgroove.co.uk !

Subject: [sfraves] DJ Bam (revu)

so i'm over here reading my statistics book... and i decide to pop in my
DJ Bam cd.  two words:  good call

Solid smooth mixing.  Intensity and volume and energy are all @ a constant
level.  this is not easy to achieve.
lots of interesting trippy sounds (is this the nu skool breaks sound
everyone has been talking about?).
so there are just some constant breaks moving to and fro; syncopating yet
keeping perfect time.  i feel my head moving independent of my volition.
atmospheric breakdowns with gentle loving vocals.  this is nice.
there are also some compressed basslines rubbing me the right way.  my
noggin' is nodding to the music.  these are the breaks.  never making my
ears bleed, yet never letting me sit down for even 1 minute.  driving
motivating force.
thanks DJ Bam.
do yourself a favor get a copy or better yet, like jack lord said, "book
'em Dan-O!"
after listening to this work, i gotta get back in the lab and make myself
mix better.

oh yeah, a Hell ova guy too from what i could gather from our brief
meeting, but you all probably already knew that.

i was raised on simply jeff breaks and this guy DJ Bam takes no shorts.

love,
j0nas

>noggin' is nodding to the music.  these are the breaks.  never making my

Subject: [sfraves] BSP (I think) -- Summer Dance Sessions 2004

so like 3-4 years ago... Ranger & I had come up w/ this idea since
him & I Love Dancing so much, ya know... why don't we get a studio 4 a
few afternoons in a row & just dance in there with hella people...
exchange moves, learn new moves, just fuckin' dance, ya
know!!

Then i thought2 myself, after we had that Awesome fuckin' conversation lastnight, why can't it happen now, the dance sessions we always talked about...  I
mean... I know of a few studios where we could do this either 4 free
or like small fee 2 rent the dance studio... but I am totally down 2
do this!!  

I mean...  we can work out details about where, when, how
& shit later per people interest ... but man... I got a burning desire 2 do
this!!

OK... a lil' about me... I attended dances classes in Napa 4 a company called TJazunique like back in the day... & then I eventually became like an assistant choreograper 4 the company... LoL... unfortunately that happened after we had our 1st & only show/fundraiser & all the routines me & Flea (the head choreographer) compiled after that were jus routines 2 teach people 4 fun!!!  I also 2 like 2 Semesters of begining Jazz dance in college.. so i'm pretty famile w/ some Jazz steps & basics & shit..  

I mean.. we can take this as far as y'all wanna take it when this all get's worked out... but I'm itchin' hard 2 teach a small routine & we can like perform it or something... but mainly jus 2 get 2gether 2 dance & do stuff! =)  LoL  I mean... this is all beginner stuff that I do choreograph if interested & from all
the Awesome talent I see from y'all on the floor, i know it wouldn't
be hard 2 do some technical steps if we do this, ya
know?

So what do y'all think???  Wanna make this happen? =)  RANGER... U better still be down w/ this Homie 'cause you're the reason I wanna do this now man! LoL  LoL... if not.. don't make me talk about old skool shit 2 u on the phone again 2 get u embarrassed like i did lastnight :P

OK.. tell me what y'all think =)

MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Help With Streaming MP3's please

You can't stream music over a dialup connection. You need to find a server
that's connected to the net on a fast link, and stream off that.
Alternately, drop the dialup and get a broadband connection such as DSL or
cable modem. You'll be able to have anywhere from 1-5 simultaneous
listeners depending on the upstream speed of the connection you end up
with, and on the quality (bitrate) of the stream you serve.

> so i'm over here reading my statistics book... and i decide to pop in my
> DJ Bam cd.  two words:  good call
> 
> Solid smooth mixing.  Intensity and volume and energy are all @ a constant
> level.  this is not easy to achieve.
> lots of interesting trippy sounds (is this the nu skool breaks sound
> everyone has been talking about?).
> so there are just some constant breaks moving to and fro; syncopating yet
> keeping perfect time.  i feel my head moving independent of my volition.
> atmospheric breakdowns with gentle loving vocals.  this is nice.
> there are also some compressed basslines rubbing me the right way.  my
> noggin' is nodding to the music.  these are the breaks.  never making my
> ears bleed, yet never letting me sit down for even 1 minute.  driving
> motivating force.
> thanks DJ Bam.
> do yourself a favor get a copy or better yet, like jack lord said, "book
> 'em Dan-O!"

Osby,

	At my regular gym (24 Hour Fitness on Market Street), there is a=20=

studio where sometimes I see people practicing dance moves when there=20
aren't classes going on. Basically it's a room with mirrors and a=20
hardwood floor.

	If you're not a 24 Hour Fitness member, I think you can go any =
time as=20
a non-member by paying $10 or $15, though obviously that's pretty=20
expensive as a long-term solution. You can generally try it for free on=20=

a one-time basis after filling out some paperwork and getting the=20
"tour"; there are also often coupons you can find which will give you=20
like a week or 10 days free if you are a local. A former SFRaver, Minh=20=

Q. Le, works the front desk sometimes. I don't know how much control he=20=

has over what kind of music they play, but I think I've noticed hearing=20=

techno with greater than usual frequency during his shift.  8)

	The studio space would be all right for a small party too, at =
least in=20
terms of being well sound-proofed. I can just see asking the management=20=

about offering a "dance fitness class" for non-members in the middle of=20=

the night, and having a guy downstairs discreetly selling tickets at=20
the door to anybody lacking a gym card. I'm sure they'd never go for=20
it, although in the past they have occasionally had DJs spinning live=20
in the gym during busy times. For those who may be looking for a chance=20=

to play out in a situation where you don't have to get everything=20
right, I imagine they're probably still open to such, although given=20
how they skimp on everything else I seriously doubt you'd even get free=20=

workouts out of the deal.

Groove on,

> 
> > You can't stream music over a dialup connection.
> You need to find a server
> > that's connected to the net on a fast link, and
> stream off that.
> > Alternately, drop the dialup and get a broadband
> connection such as DSL or
> > cable modem. You'll be able to have anywhere from
> 1-5 simultaneous
> > listeners depending on the upstream speed of the
> connection you end up
> > with, and on the quality (bitrate) of the stream
> you serve.

I'm sorry, but Oakenfold has actually had his moments, I've heard him spin
good sets in the past, and I've heard him spin very technically on point.
I've also heard him blow monkey chunks and he obviously will sell his soul
for a few more $, but at least his hype is based around being a very strong
industry presence.  Keoki is and always has been a complete joke, media hype
driven by his "attitude", connections, and appearance.  He's on the level of
Portia Surreal (the naked dj) for me...his productions suck, his dj skills
suck, and his track selection, ugh...last I saw him was in Chicago in the
mid 90's, and he passed out on the decks while spinning his set, winner!

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Help With Streaming MP3's please

You can stream anytime you want using the shoutcast server program. You =
will need a faster connection then dial-up though. To find out your ip =
address just type "ipconfig" from the commant prompt window (under =
accessories). No need to set up a dedicated server for this, just run it =
when you want to stream.=20

Steve Osteen
Progressive DJ/Producer

I guess definition of *quality tracks* leaves a lot to be interpreted. If
you mean the epic trance top 40 hits of that year - you're dead on correct
with the quality tracks title.

Aside from that aspect. He's a DAT boy. *Playing live* is another term left
to interpretation. I guess to him it means - being a living human being in
the same room as a pre-recorded DAT set is playing.

Oakenfold is a marketing guy. He's worked the market to offer easy to please
mixes for everyone needing to feel a bit of plur. His sets are like training
wheels for new kids getting into things. Technically his mixes are
lackluster and demonstrate basic bedroom dj level skills. Expect no wonders
from Oakenfold. Expect just the bare minimum status quo.

singing/rapping thang. I don't expect there's much demand for a second album.

seen a good collection of videos that included some drum & bass, but yeah

From: Starchild <sfdreamer@earthlink.net>
To: Oby Jamz <osby@hellokitty.com>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] BSP (I think) -- Summer Dance Sessions 2004
Date: Thu, 25 Mar 2004 02:05:55 -0800

Osby,

	At my regular gym (24 Hour Fitness on Market Street), there is a studio 
where sometimes I see people practicing dance moves when there aren't 
classes going on. Basically it's a room with mirrors and a hardwood floor.

	If you're not a 24 Hour Fitness member, I think you can go any time as a 
non-member by paying $10 or $15, though obviously that's pretty expensive as 
a long-term solution. You can generally try it for free on a one-time basis 
after filling out some paperwork and getting the "tour"; there are also 
often coupons you can find which will give you like a week or 10 days free 
if you are a local. A former SFRaver, Minh Q. Le, works the front desk 
sometimes. I don't know how much control he has over what kind of music they 
play, but I think I've noticed hearing techno with greater than usual 
frequency during his shift.  8)

	The studio space would be all right for a small party too, at least in 
terms of being well sound-proofed. I can just see asking the management 
about offering a "dance fitness class" for non-members in the middle of the 
night, and having a guy downstairs discreetly selling tickets at the door to 
anybody lacking a gym card. I'm sure they'd never go for it, although in the 
past they have occasionally had DJs spinning live in the gym during busy 
times. For those who may be looking for a chance to play out in a situation 
where you don't have to get everything right, I imagine they're probably 
still open to such, although given how they skimp on everything else I 
seriously doubt you'd even get free workouts out of the deal.

Groove on,
					<<< Starchild >>>

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: [FDA Wants you to know] possible suicide 10 popular antidepressants 

-------------------------------1080251665
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="US-ASCII"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

I just though I would key some people in on the facts that the FDA would like 
us to know about the 10 most popular antidepressants pills that are linked to 
suicide. I hope no one on this list kills them self or anything like that due 
to antidepressants pills. Well read up kids and have a great day 
The FDA is issuing a warning about the possibility of worsening depression or 
suicidal thoughts in people, particularly children, who take any of 10 
popular antidepressants, especially at the beginning of treatment or when the doses 
are increased or decreased. 
The FDA has sent a letter to drug manufacturers requesting labeling changes 
on these antidepressants -- warning of possible suicide, worsening depression, 
anxiety, and panic attacks in adults and children. 
Antidepressants involved in this warning label request are: 
Prozac (also sold generically as fluoxetine) 
Zoloft 
Paxil 
Luvox 
Celexa 
Lexapro 
Wellbutrin 
Effexor 
Serzone 
Remeron 
"We don't know that the drugs are responsible for these behavioral changes, 
but nonetheless we're telling physicians and families to be aware of this and 
that if the behaviors do emerge, to get treatment right away," said Russell 
Katz, a director with the FDA's Center for Drug Evaluation and Research, in a 
news teleconference today. 
The proposed warning label will "include information about behavioral changes 
that may occur in patients who are prescribed antidepressant drugs," said 
Katz. 
"This applies to adult and pediatric patients and involves the potential for 
suicidal thinking or suicidal behaviors and warns the physician and family 
about any behaviors that might emerge that haven't been experienced before," he 
added. 
But the FDA stopped short of recommending people discontinue taking their 
antidepressants. 
"We specifically decided not to tell people not to use these drugs," said 
Katz. "We don't think that is necessary at this point." 
In addition to looking for signs of worsening depression, the following 
symptoms may also be a sign of a problem: 
Anxiety 
Agitation 
Panic attacks 
Insomnia 
Irritability 
Hostility 
Impulsivity 
Severe restlessness 
Mania in both adults and children being treated with antidepressants for 
major depression 
If these changes appear, treatment should be evaluated, the FDA says. 
Medications may need to be discontinued when symptoms are severe, begin abruptly, or 
if they signal a new disorder. 
There also is concern for people who have bipolar disorder (manic depression) 
but don't know it. Antidepressants have the potential for provoking a manic 
episode in these people, the FDA says. Doctors, patients, and family members 
should be on the lookout for any symptoms of mania, including feeling extremely 
happy or very irritable, inflated self-esteem, not needing as much sleep as 
usual, talking, or being more active than usual. 

-------------------------------1080251665--

Subject: [sfraves] SRR: WHY WE'RE ADDICTED TO ADDICTION 


UK: Why We're Addicted to Addiction
URL: http://www.mapinc.org/drugnews/v04/n464/a12.html
Newshawk: JimmyG
Votes: 0
Pubdate: Sun, 21 Mar 2004
Source: Observer, The (UK)
Copyright: 2004 The Observer
Contact: letters@observer.co.uk
Website: http://www.observer.co.uk/
Details: http://www.mapinc.org/media/315
Author: Amelia Hill, The Observer

WHY WE'RE ADDICTED TO ADDICTION

>From Love to Shopping, Food to Gambling, These Days Everyone Seems To Have
Some Dependency or Other Amelie Hill Reports

Ian Young spent UKP25,000 overcoming his addiction to love.  It took eight
weeks of round-the-clock rehab and a further seven weeks of intensive
therapy, but it was worth it: the addiction he claims almost destroyed his
life is finally under control.

Some have accused the 32-year-old former disc jockey of mistaking neurosis
for addiction or of giving in to outrageous self-indulgence, but he is
adamant: in Young's eyes he is a recovering addict of an impulse every bit
as dangerous as drug or alcohol dependency.

'It began when I was around 12 years old: it was essential for me to know
I was surrounded at all times by people who loved me,' he said.  'That's
normal for teenagers, but I didn't grow out of it.

'The need to be intimate with as many people as possible remained,' he
said.  'I once went to a rave with my girlfriend and found myself in a
room with six of my current mistresses.  I'm not pretending that didn't
feel fantastic, but it was completely out of control.'

By the time Young was 29 he 'realised I had to get help'.  He booked
himself into the Promis Recovery Unit in Kent for treatment for drug
addiction and stayed for 15 weeks.  'I eventually regained my sanity and
that's when I realised the drugs had never been my primary addiction; that
has always been love,' he said.  'I know it's an addiction rather than a
neurosis because my need is completely overwhelming.'

Young now considers himself to be a recovering love addict, permanently in
danger of falling off the wagon.  'I realise I have an emotional disease;
my brain is just wired differently to other people,' he said.  'I thank my
lucky stars I discovered rehab in time; without it, I would never have
survived.'

Young is not alone in his praise: rehab has never been so used, by so
many.  The Priory Group is experiencing such a boost in numbers that it is
planning to float itself on the Stock Exchange within three to five years,
once it has doubled its 2,400-bed capacity and increased turnover, which
has already grown from UKP108.9 million in 2001 to UKP120m in 2002.

The Promis Unit books 3,000 addicts a week into its stringent six-week
course.  NHS rehab units are just as busy, with UKP573m spent on drug
treatment and UKP95m on alcohol treatment by the Government each year.

But is rehab being abused? Are these figures proof of a sick society,
desperate for salvation, or is the rush to rehab becoming an addiction in
itself?

The answer divides psychiatrists into two camps: those who believe
twenty-first century society is spawning a new range of serious addictions
focused around pleasurable activities, including mobile phone texting,
video games and eating fast food; and those who have no time for such
dependencies.

Dr Phillip Hodson, a fellow of the British Association for Counselling and
Psychotherapy, occupies the latter camp.  'I groan to the bottom of my
therapeutic shoes at this sort of discussion,' he said.  'It is misleading
to ascribe the term "addiction" to emotions.

'As a therapist, I have the greatest problem with the glib labelling of
behaviour as "addictions", where these have no obvious physiological
component beyond a reaction to our own body chemistry,' he said.  'Our
bodies contain any number of hormones that without self-control will
"cause" us to rob, rape and kill.  I don't think we really want to
encourage the idea that our centre of control, in many ways the essence of
our very humanity, can be selectively disregarded.'

Hodson says he was infuriated by the recent announcement by Petrina
Khashoggi, daughter of former Minister Jonathan Aitken, who claimed that
not only is she to join a love addicts' support group, but that her
illness forces her to share her traumas with the public.  The 23-year-old
model, who once admitted being so addicted to cannabis that it nearly
destroyed her life, said: 'The saddest thing is that I don't seem to be
able to sort out my issues in private.'

Her statement is, Hodson believes, simply another step in Britain's steady
march towards becoming a nation of addiction addicts, where celebrities
jostle to declare ever more extraordinary addictions which demand constant
rehab.

Not satisfied with winning her high-profile battle with cocaine, Tara
Palmer-Tompkinson, the former 'It Girl', also confessed to an addiction to
shopping.  Paul Gascoigne, a self-confessed alcoholic who also suffers
from an obsessive compulsive disorder, last week took to the tabloids to
announce his addiction to the caffeine-rich energy drink Red Bull - he is
said to knock back five cans an hour.

Not all the experts are as unsympathetic as Hodson.  Mark Griffiths, a
professor of gambling studies at Nottingham Trent University, who has
researched addictive behaviour for 16 years, believes any activity can
produce chemicals in the brain that give the same high as cocaine.  'We
are living in the most addictive society the world has yet seen,' he said.
'Society has changed dramatically in the last few years; we're living
longer than ever before, we have more spare time, more disposable income
and there are more socially excessive behaviours in which we can indulge.

'The biggest impact is technology, which is deliberately designed to
mesmerise the user and manipulate their behaviour.  It's exactly what
happens with addiction: you become de-sensitised and end up needing more.'

According to the Government, at least one in 25 British people is
dependent on alcohol, twice as many as are dependent on drugs, while
almost one in four of us boasts an addiction to shopping, a rise of more
than 6 per cent in just five years.

More than 370,000 Britons are addicted to gambling, while 6 per cent of
17,251 respondents in a recent online survey met the criteria for
compulsive internet use, with over 30 per cent using the net to escape
negative feelings.

Hodson is critical of the therapy industry for its open-door policy.
'It's the definition of addiction that is on the increase, not the numbers
of those genuinely addicted to anything,' he said.  'It is very
distressing to be a compulsive gambler, but addiction is not the right
word to describe what is, in fact, a conditioned or compulsive behaviour.'

Hodson also points to the tendency of psychiatrists to classify patterns
of behaviour or compulsion.  'The word addiction contains a meaning which
takes away the sufferer's freedom of action,' he added.  'It is a
destructive word if misapplied.  If you are told that you're someone who
chooses to do things that are destructive, you have more hope of recovery
than if you're told you have no choice.'

Robert Lefever, director of the Promis Recovery Centre, which only treats
those suffering alcohol, drug and food dependencies, agrees: 'There is an
addicted population and a stupid population.  There are people who just
need to pull themselves together and those who are so dependent on their
drug that they're just trying to stay alive.'

Lefever blames the stretching definition of addiction on the private and
state sectors of industry.  'We are getting consultants vying for
significance by arguing the disease they treat is more significant than
any other,' he said.  'In the private sector, that is increased by
moneymen desperately trying to find ways to increase their business.'

Dr Austin Tate, medical director at the Priory Hospital in Marchwood,
Hampshire, is bullish in his defence of the Priory's open-door policy.
'The word addiction has been so misused that it has lost its value,' he
agrees.  'Like "stress" and "depression", they've all become shorthand for
"I'm unhappy".  It's become a social description and the medical
profession needs to move away from it.

'But focusing on precise classifications is a waste of time: why make
things difficult for ourselves by arguing about it?' he asked.  'When you
get to the point of treatment, it doesn't make any difference whether
something is a dependency or an addiction,' he said.

To Lefever that distinction is not the point: 'I'm not saying people can't
be addicted to text messaging just that I don't care if they are,' he
said.

'It is a doctor's job sometimes to make moral judgements.  I don't care
what gets called addiction, as long as we recognise that compared to a
drug, alcohol or food addiction, any other compulsion is trivial.'
MAP posted-by: Richard Lake

From sfraves-return-111241-sfraves-archive=hyperreal.org@hyperreal.org Thu Mar 25 22:18:19 2004
Return-Path: <sfraves-return-111241-sfraves-archive=hyperreal.org@hyperreal.org>

Date: Thu, 25 Mar 2004 14:18:18 -0800 (PST)
From: Karina <karina@hyperreal.org>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Message-ID: <20040325141714.D80135@taz3.hyperreal.org>
SFRaves<-_->http: //www.sfraves.org
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
X-Spam-Rating: localhost.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] SRR: News - The Ecstacy Factor

(This is an extension of the original news regarding the first scientific
study of ecstacy approved since it became a controlled substance) -

US: The Ecstasy Factor
URL: http://www.mapinc.org/drugnews/v04/n407/a06.html
Newshawk: http://www.cannabisnews.com/
Votes: 1
Pubdate: Wed, 10 Mar 2004
Source: Village Voice (NY)
Copyright: 2004 Village Voice Media, Inc
Contact: editor@villagevoice.com
Website: http://www.villagevoice.com/
Details: http://www.mapinc.org/media/482
Author: Carla Spartos
Cited: Multidisciplinary Association for Psychedelic Studies
http://www.maps.org/
Bookmark: http://www.mapinc.org/people/Rick+Doblin
Bookmark: http://www.mapinc.org/people/George+Ricaurte
Bookmark: http://www.mapinc.org/people/Alan+Leshner
Bookmark: http://www.mapinc.org/mdma.htm (Ecstasy)
Bookmark: http://www.mapinc.org/find?231 (Illicit Drug Anti-Proliferation
Act (RAVE))

Bad Science Slandered a Generation's Favorite Drug.  Now a New Study Aims
to Undo the Damage.

THE ECSTASY FACTOR

Today is different: You're speaking to a psychiatrist--not in a sterile,
fluorescent-lit hospital, but in a residential office on a peaceful,
tree-lined street.  You suffer from post-traumatic stress disorder, and
you've talked for hours in this very room, but always skipping the violent
chapter that keeps you up at night, giving you flashbacks and causing you
to feel estranged from your loved ones.  Now an emergency room doctor and
nurse are stationed inside the house.  You've brought an overnight bag.
Today, you've been given 125 milligrams of Ecstasy, and maybe, just maybe,
you'll finally be able to face your demons.

On February 24, the DEA issued Dr.  Michael Mithoefer a Schedule I license
to legally obtain Ecstasy for a study of its potential therapeutic effects
in the treatment of PTSD.  Researchers hope that the drug, which melts
anxiety, will help PTSD patients talk openly about the experiences that
scarred them.  It is the first study of Ecstasy-enhanced psychotherapy
ever green-lighted in the United States, one that's been in the making for
almost two decades.  "There's been so much struggle over this approval
process," says Rick Doblin, director of MAPS, the Multidisciplinary
Association for Psychedelic Studies, the organization sponsoring the
research.

Doblin's group stands to create a new landscape for Ecstasy, which has
been at the center of the nation's war on drugs.  The old one--with its
hidden agendas, career-obsessed scientists, powerful patrons, and switched
pills--has only recently been scorched.  It all began in September, when
the journal Science published a retraction from a group of Johns Hopkins
scientists who'd discovered that a bottle they thought contained Ecstasy
was in fact filled with methamphetamine, commonly known as speed.  The
mix-up corrupted the results of a study, published in Science in September
2002, which found that a single, recreational dose of Ecstasy was so
damaging it could lead to Parkinson's disease.  Another study, published
in the European Journal of Pharmacology, would also be recalled.

The British journal Nature promptly published an editorial dubbing the
incident "one of the more bizarre episodes in the history of drug
research." Colin Blakemore, head of the U.K.'s Medical Research Council (
the British equivalent of the National Institutes of Health ), demanded
that an independent inquiry be conducted into the affair.  And The New
York Times' Donald G.  McNeil Jr.  wrote a scathing indictment of the
study's lead scientist, George Ricaurte, alleging "a pattern of shaky
research supporting alarmist press releases."

Ricaurte did not respond to repeated messages left on his voice mail at
Johns Hopkins or to an official request through Johns Hopkins
representatives, but he has long been dismissive of his work's critics.
In 2001, he told the Voice, "Everyone in the field has accepted [MDMA] is
a neurotoxin.  I think those [dissenting] arguments have to be put in
perspective." It is this unyielding conviction that has been the hallmark
of Ricaurte's career as the nation's foremost Ecstasy researcher.

But critics say the science has been less than convincing.  Ecstasy
promotes strong feelings of empathy by flooding the brain with serotonin,
a feel-good neurotransmitter manipulated by drugs like Prozac.  Once the
high wears off, users register markedly depleted serotonin levels for
about two weeks.  What is not known--and thus is hotly debated--is whether
these changes presage permanent brain damage.

That debate seemed settled when Science issued a press release in
September 2002 announcing the devastating results of Ricaurte's study:
After taking doses of Ecstasy akin to what teens might take at a rave, 60
to 80 percent of dopamine-related neurons in the test monkeys' brains were
destroyed.  The release was picked up in headlines around the globe.  But
some of those who got around to reading the actual study say what they
found troubled them.

"The press release deliberately misrepresented the data," says Colin
Blakemore.  "There was no evidence of the 60 to 80 percent cell-death
claim." There were other red flags: 20 percent of the monkeys had died;
another 20 percent had gotten so sick they had to be withdrawn.  Yet there
simply aren't thousands of people dying from Ecstasy every weekend.  Then
there was the problem that the drugs were injected--not administered
orally as suggested in the paper's introduction.

"The more I looked at it, the more I felt there was an agenda," says
Blakemore, who immediately fired off a letter to Science editor in chief
Donald Kennedy, complaining of "flaws so radical, so deep, they would have
been picked up by any referee." But Science maintains it did everything
right.  "This study was peer-reviewed according to the same rigorous
system used in all articles published in Science," says Ginger Pinholster,
spokesperson for the Association for the Advancement of Science, which
publishes the journal.  According to Pinholster, the prompt retraction
proved that "science is self-correcting."

Public policy, however, is not so mutable.  Weeks after the botched study
was published, its conclusions were repeatedly invoked by witnesses at a
House subcommittee hearing on the Reducing Americans' Vulnerability to
Ecstasy Act ( RAVE Act ).  The bill was quietly passed last April as the
slightly reworded Illicit Drug Anti-Proliferation Act.  Aimed at quelling
club drugs like Ecstasy and GHB, the law permits the prosecution of venue
owners and club promoters for drug use on their premises.  Only a month
after it became law, it was used by a federal agent to shut down a benefit
for Students for Sensible Drug Policy and the National Organization for
the Reform of Marijuana Laws.  And last weekend, it was used to shutter
the Sound Factory nightclub in Manhattan.

As easy as it is to paint Ricaurte as a rogue scientist motivated by
ambition, the scientific establishment and its patrons also played key
roles in the wider scandal, from merely ignoring critical flaws to
blatantly promoting problematic studies.  Alan Leshner, publisher of
Science and former director of the National Institute on Drug Abuse ( NIDA
), has come under fire for endorsing the botched study at its time of
publication.  "It isn't clear why an officer of the AAAS should be
involved at all in publicly promoting a particular result published in its
journal, least of all one whose outcome was questioned at the outset by
several experts," wrote Nature.  Pinholster says she called upon her boss
"to serve as an expert source as a service to reporters," adding, "There
was no conspiracy." Leshner declined to be interviewed.

Leshner has long railed against the dangers of Ecstasy.  In 2001, when he
was director of NIDA, he told the Voice, "We've known since the late '80s
that MDMA can damage serotonin neurons, and if you give enough of it,
they're blown away."

Rick Doblin, on the eve of his own study, says the payoffs for such shoddy
science have been immense.  "Leshner was willing to exaggerate findings to
pander to politicians for money," he says.  Leshner did help NIDA bring
home the bacon: NIDA's budget for Ecstasy research has more than
quadrupled over the past five years, from $3.4 million to $15.8 million;
the agency funds 85 percent of the world's drug-abuse research.  In 2001,
Leshner testified before a Senate subcommittee on "Ecstasy Abuse and
Control"; critics say Leshner manipulated brain scans from a 2000 study by
Dr.  Linda Chang showing no difference between Ecstasy users and control
subjects.  But NIDA insists it's independent from political pressures.
"We don't set policy; we don't create laws," says Beverly Jackson, the
agency's spokesperson.

NIDA wasn't the only benefactor of Ricaurte and wife Una McCann's
research.  "George and Una are cash cows for Johns Hopkins," says Doblin,
who points out that every time a scientist receives a grant, money
indirectly goes to the affiliated institution.  While both NIDA and The
New York Times have clocked Ricaurte's NIDA grant money at around $10
million, Doblin believes that's a low-ball figure.  "Just this one study
was $1.3 million, and he has done loads and loads of them." Johns Hopkins
spokesperson Gary Stevenson declined comment beyond the official
statement.

Another consequence of the retracted study and other discredited
NIDA-funded findings is that they've helped obstruct legitimate research
into the possible medical benefits of Ecstasy.  Doblin believes Ricaurte
and others are threatened by such research because it doesn't square with
their drug-war agenda.  In the past, Leshner has balked at those
accusations.  "It frankly bugs me," he told the Voice in 2001.  "It's easy
to say that the government isn't approving studies because they're
politically incorrect.  The government may say yes."

Now that the government--more specifically, the FDA--has indeed said yes,
Doblin's research into the benefits of Ecstasy in treating post-traumatic
stress disorder is under way.  The $300,000 MAPS project, which is funded
by private individuals and family foundations, has had some major setbacks
since it initially received FDA approval in November 2001.  The study was
to have been conducted at the Medical University of South Carolina before
that institution backed out; it will now be held in a private doctor's
office.  While Doblin believes the program would have gotten off the
ground without Ricaurte's retraction, he says it's made all the players,
including the institutional review board and insurance company, "feel a
lot more comfortable."

A study under way in Spain examining the potential therapeutic effects of
Ecstasy in rape victims hasn't fared as well.  The Madrid Anti-Drug
Authority pressured the sponsoring hospital to shut the study down in May
2002.  Doblin largely blames Ricaurte for the mounting difficulties the
research team has faced since then: Ricaurte, who was born in Ecuador, is
fluent in Spanish, and gave four talks in Spain presenting his bungled
findings.

As for the Illicit Drug Anti-Proliferation Act, Margaret Aitken, press
secretary for Senator Joseph Biden, who sponsored the bill, said, "Senator
Biden will not change his position based on this one [retracted] study." A
Senate aide also confirmed the legislation would not be revisited, and
that there's "no official process to go back and correct the record."

Blakemore, meanwhile, is still calling for a "full and open discussion"
from Science, including the disclosure of the paper's referee reports.
"If the referees didn't spot what I noticed right away, then what does
that say about the quality of [Science's] referees?" asks Blakemore.  "And
if the referees did make negative comments [that went unheeded], what does
that say about Science?" At press time, Blakemore and Leslie Iversen, an
Oxford University pharmacologist, were drafting a letter that Don Kennedy
has promised to publish in Science.  That journal, NIDA, and Johns Hopkins
insist there's been no evidence of foul play; no investigations were being
conducted at any of these institutions at press time.

In the end, the ones most negatively affected by the studies may be those
they purport to help.  "I'm very concerned about drug use, but the way to
tackle it is not to misrepresent scientific evidence," says Blakemore.
"What's going to be the impact of these studies? Young people won't
believe anything they read."


MAP posted-by: Larry Seguin

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] WHAT'S THE BEST WAY TO RIP DVDs?

We're talking about recompression into a suitable format for viewing and
archiving. Any of those dual layer to one layer shrink apps will still
produce files that are 4GB in size. That's a quick way to fill a HD. The
ideal way is to make them all into DivX 5, or XViD format. These are
compression codecs for video, the audio streams for both is MP3. By
compressing with one of these you get the core movie (none of that menu
crap) and a file that's 700MB to a little over 1GB depending on the quality
settings you choose.

If you want to learn more - google "dvd to divx" and you will find a
plethora of information on what tools you need and how it's all done.

:: r ::

for THUMP CHILL.

5pm - 10pm  
                             
With a chill vibe and a cozy ANU atmosphere - THUMP CHILL will
ease you into the weekend.
 
Plus...it's FREE, that's right FREE, FREE, FREE !   Along with
rockin' food specials and drink specials!
 
Let Shari take away the worries of the week with one of her
wonderful Massages. 
 
How can you resist?  This is one hell of a fun and relaxing
happy hour!

Jondi, Forest Green, 0llijude, Holmes, Alex Whalen and many
more.  We have a lot more on the horizon, every week more and
more DJ's that normally play house or progressive keep coming
in and saying they want to spin some chill.  

Also thanks to our friends and supporters.   
 
LINEUP FOR Friday March 26th, 2004

Masonic (thump radio)
Sinukus (thump radio / funky cozy) 
 
And our very special guests : 
Redstickman and Speakeasy Ray from the Ambient Mafia

why Djs like Keoki and Oakenfold being touted as superhuman pisses a lot
of people off.  If the name of the game is style, skill, originality and
consistency they're past where they should be popularity-wise.

Importance: Normal

Subject: RE: [sfraves] NRR: Ripping audio from video

I don't believe that soundforge can get the audio from within any movie
formats. I think you'll need a movie program like Adobe's Premiere or
something of that ilk to separate them in to different files. You could
always just try playing the movie in a media player and then using
soundforge to record the audio coming through your computers internal
bus - if your soundcard/machine can handle that. It's kinda a hack, but
it'd work.

-Aaron

dina rox, andy rollz.

AndyW <andy@saturn5.com> said...
> p.s.  Best is silly.  I think there are DJs that stand apart based on
> selection, technique, experience and being able to connect with various
> vibes... nobody's got it all.  Also, any DJ can have a good night, but you
> sorta come to expect that the best don't have totally bad nights which is
> why Djs like Keoki and Oakenfold being touted as superhuman pisses a lot
> of people off.  If the name of the game is style, skill, originality and
> consistency they're past where they should be popularity-wise.

What he said.

And my own spin is...

It's not about the Hokie Pokey.
It's not about popularity.
It's not about being sexy.
It's not about friends.
It's not about PLUR.
It's not about the drugs.
It's not about the music.
It's not about the DJ.
It's not about technical skills.
It's not about track selection.

You wanna impress our asses??? You wanna be talked about for 10
years?

MAKE US DANCE OUR FUCKING BOOTIES OFF.

Make us deeply resentful that we have to go to the bathroom. Make
us wish all our friends were there. Take us somewhere so deep it
takes a week to get back. Make us think you're utterly insane and
utterly connected to the crowd.

Make

Us

Dance

*That* is the art of the DJ.

Subject: [sfraves] SFRCal: 03.26.04

Magic is a set of techniques and approaches which can be used to extend
the limits of Achievable Reality. Our sense of Achievable Reality is the
limitations we believe bind us into a narrow range of actions and
successes - what we believe to be possible for us at any one time. In
this context, the purpose of magic is to simultaneously explore those
boundaries and attempt to push them back, to widen - the "Sphere" of
possible action.

- Phil Hine

To remove your address from the list, send a message to:
sfraves-calendar-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org

Send mail to the following for info and FAQ for this list:
sfraves-calendar-info@hyperreal.org or
sfraves-calendar-faq@hyperreal.org

Subject: [sfraves] BSP:  Remember The Party

--=====================_11465466==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

A group of us from the former Trocadero Transfer have gotten together and
decided to have a retro dance at The Glas Kat (formerly Trocadero Transfer).
The event will be a Tea Dance on Sunday April 18, 2004, form 6:00 pm until
2:00 am. We will have D.J. Robbie Leslie (www.robbieleslie.com) from The
Saint, Studio 54,and the  Palladium coming in from Fla. to play the event.
There will also be two of the original Trocadero lighting people working the
lights and arc lamp. Our music venue will be from the mid 70's through the
mid 80's.

Our web address is: www.remembertheparty.com, or you can call our event line
at: (415) 339-7807. Our site is fully functional with all the sponsors and
links to their sites. We now also have advance On-Line ticket sales. A
portion of the proceeds will go to benefit Under One Roof. We are also
thinking of doing a raffle where all the proceeds will go to Under One Roof.
Items in the raffle may include Varsity jackets from Bear Built Tough, an
audio cd recording of the event itself, tee-shirts of the event, 5 Trocadero
remix cd's, Starbucks has donated a huge gift basket of their products and
Medium Rare Records has offered to donate a $50.00 gift certificate as well.
We are going to talk to Under One Roof about displaying the raffle
merchandise at their store and selling raffle tickets in advance, as well as
some of their own merchandise for sale up stairs at the event.

At this time we have just put out word of mouth and handed out some teaser
flyer's for the event and have received over 5,000 hits on our site this
month alone. I am looking forward to what the response will be when we start
to advertise fully this week.

We would like to invite you to our event. This tea Dance is for a good cause
and I personally think you will really enjoy the event yourself.

If you are not familiar with Robbie Leslie, please go to his site and have a
look. He has been spinning for over 25 years and is still quite flawless.
Robbie has always been referred to as "The Gentleman Of Disco." His programs
and mixes are legendary.

We are hoping to have lots of fan and flag dancers join in the festivities
as we have a good size stage.  Also we would like to encourage any one who
has tambourines, finger symbols, whistles, claves or any percussion
instruments to please join us and help make the night more festive! What
made the Trocadero Transfer magic was that it was the ultimate in sound,
light and space but most of all it was the group of people that came
together to celebrate the dance.




Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm
