the children of humans as a whole experience it.  Avoiding danger is no 
safer in the long run than outright exposure.  Life is either a daring 
adventure or nothing."
-Helen Keller

The dangerous patriot: "The one who drifts into chauvinism and exhibits 
blind enthusiasm for military actions. He is a defender of militarism and 
its ideals of war and glory. Chauvinism is a proud and bellicose form of 
patriotism . . . which identifies numerous enemies who can only be dealt 
with through military power and which equates the national honor with 
military victory..."
-Marine Corps, Colonel James A. Donovan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

I have never seen turntablism like that before live. Holy shit. I think =
I just stood there wide eyed for most of the time. Bastids make it look =
so easy. I loved the setup of the main room. One of the most unique =
setups I've seen since Halloween there. Music selection for all of the =
rooms was on spot. I don't remember disliking anything I heard that =
night. Rather rare these days. Oh and the sound. The sound geek in me =
gives the sound a 9. I loved that they hung 4 corner audio in the main =
room. I haven't seen any crew hang their setups from the ceiling in =
there. That really did wonders for that room. As always Gateway in the =
breaks//jungle room gave every inch of your body a thourough massage, =
but never hurt your ears. Don's system in the dub room up top was =
perfect for the room size and genre.

Very well done party that went above and beyond what you would expect =
from a loosely managed event. For $10 no less too. Hell - someone even =
provided Jamaican food in the dub room!

If only those shitty little *crews* that throw *undergrounds* in SF =
would pull their heads out of their greedy asses and do something like =
this...

:: r ::

Subject: RE: [sfraves] :: woah :: otherworld.this.weekend

Yea - despite me having a HORRIBLE Saturday afternoon, I managed to salvage 
the day by going to the Otherworld and partying down a bit (nice seein' ya 
again Ryan!).

I wasn't super-impressed with the 1st acts in the main and front rooms to be 
honest. They sounded a little sloppy for my taste, but the place warmed up 
as people rolled in, and the talent increased enormously.

Freaky Chakra busted out some sick beats, and Azeem & Zeph were soooooooooo 
on point. The cats that went on after Azeem were also pretty damn good. I 
will have to agree with Ryan that some of the turntablism that went on was 
dope.

My favorite area all night was the dub/dancehall room though. For as 
"african american" a city as Washington DC is, there's not a huge dud scene 
at all. So for me, it's a treat to go out and hear some nice pulsing, heady 
dub.

Otherworld really did up the decor this time I thought. The place was really 
well organized and set-up.

Two thumbs up for letting me loosen up on Saturday night!!!

Marc(O)

Subject: [sfraves] (Review) Furious

	I am a very easy to please person. It doesn't take much for me to have 
fun someplace, but this party didn't even meet my low standards. I made 
it until about 1:30 and then I had to bounce because I couldn't take it 
anymore. It was so hot and stuffy, and they put the big fan pointed down 
the hallway, which meant that if you needed air, you had to block 
traffic. The bathrooms were 2 porta-pottys in the smoking room. Indoor 
outhouses! I haven't seen this done since the Sweets Ballroom. Yes, this 
was my first time at the Bush and Van Ness venue, and I will not go to 
another party there. Water was $2, and the only place to refill your 
water bottle was from a foot pumped sink in each porta-potty. Right. No 
way in hell I'm gonna drink out of that. Security was overly aggressive 
and intimidating. Music-wise, Brandon (BAM), Forest Green, Madam Mercury 
and Denise all ripped it up. It was so hot and packed that  I kept going 
room to room, but I finally decided that I wasn't going to find 
satisfaction anywhere at this party. A lot of people were on drugs, but 
I can't imagine doing drugs there and enjoying myself. I talked to some 
people who were having bad trips, and I knew that it was because of 
their environment. I did see a bunch of people that I knew including 
Osby, Brenna, Sheztek, Tyler, Marshal, Abby, Kx-Kx, Disconnect, Chel-C, 
Casino and others. They were the best part of this night, but I finally 
had enough and had to bounce. There's nothing like getting harassed by 
tranny hookers as you make your way back to your car after a shitty 
party. It was one of those "Oh yeah, that's why I stopped going to 
parties that sell tickets at Skills" kind of nights.

Subject: [sfraves]  Look what I made this weekend (excercise in cheapness)

The psycedelic black velvet I picked up at the fabric store for real =
cheap. It hides my bad woodworking skills.
I glued the fabric to the wood using auto upulstry(sp?) spray glue and a =
staple gun.
The wood was just 2 cheap 4' x 4' pieces and some scraps from home =
depot.

I spent a total of ~$60 on materials for the table.
=20
That amp sitting under the table is my Heathkit (old skool hi-fi) =
receiver I picked up at the flea market for $40.=20
The speakers are freebies that were being thrown out by a family =
memeber.
The DJCD dual player is a factory referbished(it works and looks =
perfect) unit that I got off e-bay for half the price of a new unit.
The mixer I bought off a friend for half the cost of a new one.
Half that vinyl I got for 25 cents at Rasputin in Fremont.

Quality of mixes made with this setup: priceless.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] :: woah :: otherworld.this.weekend

quoth innocentchild:
> Very well done party that went above and beyond what you would expect
> from a loosely managed event. For $10 no less too. Hell - someone even
> provided Jamaican food in the dub room!
> 
> If only those shitty little *crews* that throw *undergrounds* in SF
> would pull their heads out of their greedy asses and do something like
> this...

Seconded! The Otherworld really did well with this party. It was great
to hear non-commercial hip-hop at an underground, and see that people
were really into it. Inspector Double Negative fucking rocked, those
guys were hilarious. That song about DJ's was spot-on, ditching a lady
because he had to fetch a record from behind the speakers so he could
get it to the promoter before he escaped out the back door... Classic.

The dub upstairs was the perfect accompaniment to my induced state, and
it was refreshing to see an MC who knew the records and picked the right
moments to flow. Felix was bumpin' it proper with Gateway when I left,
and it looks like the party was starting to fill up. Unfortunately I
missed Freaky Chakra AGAIN... Next time I need to avoid drinking during
the day if I have any hopes of staying up all night.

I do have one critcism: the opening act in the Gateway room was too
much. You can't expect people to dance to stuff that hard so early in
the night! Other than that, top music, tasteful decour, nice crowd...
Great party!

Cheers,
-- 
shawn allen
  mailto://shawn@alterior.net
  phone://+1.415.577.3961
  http://alterior.net
  aim://shawnpallen

deep techno, dub and IDM. The deets:

Who: Shazbot, Forest Green, Clairity, and other TeknotikaSF residents
What: deep techy goodness
Where: The Canvas Gallery, 9th & Lincoln, San Francisco
When: TONIGHT, Monday night from 8pm - 12 midnight

The Canvas Gallery is a really great space. They've got good food, wine
and beer, coffee, free wi-fi access, and a nice vibe overall. Hope to
see you there!

I used to go to that venue quite a bit because I have a lot of friends that 
play there often.  I played there a few weeks ago, but I expressed a little 
bit of discontent with venue on a random BayRaves thread.  When I went the 
following weekend, the proprietor of the venue had security waiting for me 
at the bottom of the stairs.  I went from playing for free for him one 
weekend, to 86'd the next.  That's definitely not the worst story about the 
guy and his space though.  There are actually quite a few.  Here's an 
example: a friend of mine rented the space to throw a free party 
(Onieromancy) and for whatever reason (something to do with not making 
enough money at the H2O bar I believe) at the end of the night, he held his 
turntables ransom for more money.  Basically he got bent over and raped 
twice; surprisingly, that was one of the best parties that I've seen there 
as well.  Go figure.
-Joey

it clear that they can be gutted from the scene very, very easily.

no beef tho joey, you're a kool kat and i still like ya... ;)

at that kind of space are too ignorant to boycott. The number of people with
any sense of what goes on behind the scenes or what makes a venue//owner

rave lists and the mentality of their subscribers. So yeah, the sad reality
is that venues like that will exist so long as they don't get busted.

Brainchild events (remember ORGY?).=20

with the lists, sorry you will have to pay $20 to get in"=20
promoting that a party is free before 10pm (then not letting people in =
until after 10, making them stand in line outside in the cold or rain =
until that 10 o'clock hour has passed)

What ever happened to Brainchild stuff anyway, did these bad practices =
come back to destroy them or did they get busted for having securty paid =
off by the drug dealers (not that I mind that though). I use to =
blatently see the dealers handing security their cut of the money, again =
not that I minded that, at least it kept the events to only a couple =
dealers that had quality chems, but expensive.

Message-ID: <BAY12-F78Ne6YRiQgct0001c1e1@hotmail.com>

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] (Review) Furious

I understand your perspective, but I think our ideologies vary slightly:

>dood... the promoter actually did you a favor by putting you on the 
>lineup... he's been very good >with bringing out bedroom and up and coming 
>djs to play there, especially for the zodiac series >where basically 
>anybody can play their sign if they ask the right way...

I agree that it was nice getting some more time in front of a crowd and 
there is the occasional DJ on a lineup that I havent seen before, however, 
this is not the normal circumstance.  There are generally between 24 and 35 
DJs there per party, depending on how many rooms they open up and I would 
say that there are about six parties there per month.  I guess I would 
estimate that to about 30 x 6 = ~180 timeslots.   Of those ~180 timeslots, I 
may see one or two names that Im not familiar with.  On the other hand, I 
can almost always predict what the timeslots between 12-3 will be for any 
given genre.  The rest of slots seem to rotate on a bi or triweekly basis.  
As far as asking the right way, Im not sure what you mean, but it kind of 
freaks me out, lol

>when you talk nasty about the venue the next week of course he's probly 
>gonna feel at least a lil >stabbed in the back, no? you're entitled to your 
>opinion of the venue but a lil support goes a long >way, ya know...

I agree that if you stab someone in the back they should feel hurt; however, 
I, and others who were indirectly involved, saw the sarcasm in my post and 
understood the criticism.  The comment was actually less pointed at the 
venue and the proprietor than it was at the numerous promoters who continue 
to throw overpriced, cookie-cutter parties.  My original post was:
>>"I was planning on going, and then I realized that it was free. I'm so 
>>used to over-priced parties >>at the same spot with the same dj's week 
>>after week that I may not be able to adjust to this >>environment. 
>>Different DJ's?  No overpriced presales? No Door $? What is this world 
>>coming to?  >>Only drawback to this party is the venue; I know it sounds 
>>crazy, but I think I've been there >>before."
Perhaps I am wrong in assuming that people understand sarcastic criticism 
and that they can use it to better themselves, their environments, and their 
business practices.  Perhaps I am wrong in assuming that people have the 
ability to change.  Perhaps I am wrong in assuming that people actually want 
to better the environments of the patrons.  Perhaps I have lied to myself.  
In any case, I do not believe that is constructive to try to silence (or in 
this case 86) someone because they criticize things they dont agree with.  
Without criticism things become stagnant and complacency becomes the norm.  
Is there nothing more grotesque than complacency?  Look back at the efforts 
of the powerful to crush the social-protest novels in times of injustice.  
The only difference here is that we are subjecting ourselves to this heinous 
environment by supporting overpriced parties at the same stagnant dungeon.  
If one steps outside of the box there is another world.  Look at Moksha and 
Modified as examples.  Each has brought an experience at each party; more 
than just a party, but a feeling.  Modified $3 monthly in a new venue is 
amazing and the respect and treatment Moksha shows is incredible (with 
amazing talent and fresh lineups too).  Promoters should take notice, these 
crews do it right.


>as for playing for free, nobody should really be bringing up $$ their first 
>handful of gigs.

I actually totally agree with you and I dont mind playing for free.  I 
brought up the money thing because there are a lot of people that play there 
pretty consistently that dont even get kicked down gas money (even when 
they come from Sac).  Its pretty obvious that if you charge a $20 door 
cover and the place gets packed, someone is making money.  Too bad it seems 
that it always ends up in the same hands.

>no beef tho joey, you're a kool kat and i still like ya... ;)
Word, youre a good dude with good intentions I know this.  Rock on Brotha.

Sorry about the long email, had to drop another 2 cents though,
-Joey

Subject: [sfraves] About Oneiromancy + Turntables

Hi,

I'm not usually a member of this list, but someone
told me that people were saying I was complaining
about using the Dungeon spot in SF.

I threw a free party there, called Oneiromancy. As
free as the party was, the use of space, the DJs who
came out, etc wasnt. I had to pay for all that. 

Jared let me use the space for a downpayment, with the
understanding that the outstanding balance would be
paid to him once I got more money (which would be
about 2 weeks.) I had left my decks there so that the
promoters throwing a party the next night could use
them.   

Since I was leaving them there, I told Jared he could
just keep them until I paid him back. I dont really
use my decks - technically, they aren't even mine, as
I gave to my girlfriend. I dont really practice or
anything, so not having them there didnt bother me. 

So, if theres drama or whatever on here because of
that, just let me say that Jared did a favor for me,
so I did a favor for him (as he also needed decks
there for some other shows.) 

I didnt see the message that started this drama, I was
only paraphrased what it said. So thats the story of
that.

~Paul <wavelength> 
[Oneiromancy]

(PS - I'm unsubscribing from this list after I send
this. I was a member for a long time, but the signal
to noise ratio and messages like the one that was
quoted to me made me leave. If anyone wants to get in
touch with me for any reason, you can send a message
to wavelength_sf@yahoo.com )

-------------------------------1080612435
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="US-ASCII"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

Three cheers for Paul (Wavelength). Your parties, which have been either free 
or extremely low on price, have been some of the best parties I've been to in 
terms of vibe and music. Considering how many promoters lose money on parties 
even when they charge a hefty admission price, we know these parties have 
cost you a lot of money. Thanks so much! 

Also, thanks to Jared for making his space available. I think that when 
ravers find a space that can be used often, without hassles, there's a tendency to 
point out what's wrong about that space. It happened with 2nd & Jackson (too 
dirty), Maritime Hall (too clean), and many other spots. In an ideal world, the 
"dungeon" would be one of several places we could count on regularly. Some 
parties might be out in the woods or involve several map points -- that can be 
fun. However, while variety is great, it's nice to have a venue that we can 
count on. It's nice to be able to make weekend plans knowing pretty much that the 
party is going to be in a particular place. 

At the same time, some things could be better at the dungeon. I see signs of 
improvement and I hear about plans for making it better. 
I do agree that the overly testosterone'd security detracts from the vibe of 
the party; some say it's for show in case there are snitches among us. Could 
be true ... I haven't yet been to a party there that's been shut down and maybe 
a perception of "zero tolerance" helps when the cops want to know what's 
going on. 

That's it ... for my rant & rave   :)  
Thanks again, Paul

John

-------------------------------1080612435--

  This is the kind of stuff that needs to be shared more. Perhaps I'm 
the only one on this list who didn't know what this venue is like, but I 
doubt it. Had I known what to expect, I would have passed once I heard 
last week that they were going to have to use the Van Ness spot instead 
of the Sausage Factory as planned. I agree with voting with my wallet, 
but I don't want to have to assume that just because a party is all 
ages, or just because they sell tickets at Skills, that means that it's 
going to suck. I rely on word of mouth from people that I meet, but that 
alone limits the circles that I travel in. I've been finding my way to 
some psytrance parties so far this year, though I'm still pretty much 
out of the loop in that scene.

Here's where I recap my biggest complaints: Charging $2 a bottle for 
water in a cramped, hot space with no place to refill your water 
bottles, at an all ages party, and then having security get pissed off 
when some kid pukes. I understand that this was a last minute change, 
but I'm really sorry that said change fucked up what I'm sure would have 
been a fun party for me.

Happy

Subject: [sfraves] Furious

first of all, i want to thank everyone who came out the Furious.  as i said 
before the party, i knew that there were LOTS of options for parties that 
night (OW, FP...oh my! breaks even!) and i really appreciate every person 
who came out to get down with us.

as some of you mentioned, we did lose our original venue and, after 
searching for another space, decided to work with Jared.  it allowed for 
less than half the total capacity of our original space and therefore, 
changed many of the logistics of the party.

we've gotten a lot of feedback on the party. mostly positive, but of course, 
we (or atleast, i) totally understand and are open to hear constructive 
criticism.  to happy, i dig your honesty and trust me, your words are not 
falling on deaf ears.

i'm just glad that we threw down some sick breaks to a crowd of folks that 
were gettin' down.  for our first party to go off despite some 
setbacks...i'm satisfied.  the next one will be better, for sure.  we'll 
continue to grow, continue to learn and improve...and still keep dropping 
the baddest beats that we can.

again...huge thanks to everyone who made this possible.  to my homeboy aaron 
jae who put in 110% in the party, to thomas kent for supporting us, to all 
the volunteers, to the DJs, to jared, and especially..most of all, the 
people who came out.  it's been my strongest belief that a party is ALWAYS 
about the people.  the people make the vibe and the vibe makes the party.  
(music is cool too)

evil breaks and ill behavior thank you all.

On Mon, 29 Mar 2004, innocentchild wrote:

> I have never seen turntablism like that before live. Holy shit. I think I just stood there wide eyed for most of the time. Bastids make it look so easy. I loved the setup of the main room. One of the most unique setups I've seen since Halloween there. Music selection for all of the rooms was on spot. I don't remember disliking anything I heard that night. Rather rare these days. Oh and the sound. The sound geek in me gives the sound a 9. I loved that they hung 4 corner audio in the main room. I haven't seen any crew hang their setups from the ceiling in there. That really did wonders for that room. As always Gateway in the breaks//jungle room gave every inch of your body a thourough massage, but never hurt your ears. Don's system in the dub room up top was perfect for the room size and genre.
>
> Very well done party that went above and beyond what you would expect from a loosely managed event. For $10 no less too. Hell - someone even provided Jamaican food in the dub room!
>
> If only those shitty little *crews* that throw *undergrounds* in SF would pull their heads out of their greedy asses and do something like this...
>
> :: r ::

Ahem.

I'm not taking sides here. However:

Saying DJs -- the ones, you know, putting the records on the turntables
and twiddling little knobs -- are being done a favor, playing for free at
parties where the promoters are making massive quantities of money is
kinda bullshit.

S

On Mon, 29 Mar 2004, apot wrote:

> dood... i'm not calling you out nor am i taking the other side here, but look at it from this perspective... the promoter actually did you a favor by putting you on the lineup and your first flyer... he's been very good with bringing out bedroom and up and coming djs to play there, especially for the zodiac series where basically anybody can play their sign if they ask the right way... when you talk nasty about the venue the next week of course he's probly gonna feel at least a lil stabbed in the back, no? you're entitled to your opinion of the venue but a lil support goes a long way, ya know...
> as for playing for free, nobody should really be bringing up $$ their first handful of gigs. i can assure you most ppl play there for free anyway. with so many djs out there, the promoters are actually doing you a favor by inviting you to the lineup...
> no beef tho joey, you're a kool kat and i still like ya... ;)
> and yes, wavelength throws some of the coolest parties, not to mention cheap as hell!!! onieromancy r0x0rs... lol

> Joey Frisco <josephwhunt@hotmail.com> wrote:
> I used to go to that venue quite a bit because I have a lot of friends that
> play there often. I played there a few weeks ago, but I expressed a little
> bit of discontent with venue on a random BayRaves thread. When I went the
> following weekend, the proprietor of the venue had security waiting for me
> at the bottom of the stairs. I went from playing for free for him one
> weekend, to 86'd the next. That's definitely not the worst story about the
> guy and his space though. There are actually quite a few. Here's an
> example: a friend of mine rented the space to throw a free party
> (Onieromancy) and for whatever reason (something to do with not making
> enough money at the H2O bar I believe) at the end of the night, he held his
> turntables ransom for more money. Basically he got bent over and raped
> twice; surprisingly, that was one of the best parties that I've seen there
> as well. Go figure.

> > > anymore. It was so hot and stuffy, and they put the big fan pointed down
> > > the hallway, which meant that if you needed air, you had to block
> > > traffic. The bathrooms were 2 porta-pottys in the smoking room. Indoor
> > > outhouses! I haven't seen this done since the Sweets Ballroom. Yes, this
> > > was my first time at the Bush and Van Ness venue, and I will not go to
> > > another party there. Water was $2, and the only place to refill your
> > > water bottle was from a foot pumped sink in each porta-potty. Right. No
> > > way in hell I'm gonna drink out of that. Security was overly aggressive
> > > and intimidating. Music-wise, Brandon (BAM), Forest Green, Madam Mercury
> > > and Denise all ripped it up. It was so hot and packed that I kept going
> > > room to room, but I finally decided that I wasn't going to find
> > > satisfaction anywhere at this party. A lot of people were on drugs, but
> > > I can't imagine doing drugs there and enjoying myself. I talked to some
> > > people who were having bad trips, and I knew that it was because of
> > > their environment. I did see a bunch of people that I knew including
> > > Osby, Brenna, Sheztek, Tyler, Marshal, Abby, Kx-Kx, Disconnect, Chel-C,
> > > Casino and others. They were the best part of this night, but I finally
> > > had enough and had to bounce. There's nothing like getting harassed by
> > > tranny hookers as you make your way back to your car after a shitty
> > > party. It was one of those "Oh yeah, that's why I stopped going to
> > > parties that sell tickets at Skills" kind of nights.

also?

How about me, I love my QA engineer job here at Pinnacle, so I shouldn't =
get paid for it either?

Dj's should be paid for what they do, and paid Very well since I believe =
that they can make or break a party much more then any other person at =
the party. Of course a new DJ, trying to get noticed and experience has =
to play for free or cheap, but same with new pilots and new QA =
engineers.

Subject: RE: [sfraves] (Review) Furious

get over yourself.  dj's aren't that special.

its all about supply and demand--  basically, there are more kids out there 
that would like to dj than would like to get paid to dj.  what makes you 
think you deserve cash, when promoters are bringing in just enough (even 
with expensive ticket prices) to pay their top headliners, and then break 
even on the partay?  if anyone things there are promoters out there making 
"gobs of cash" on anything, than i hate to break it to you, but you are 
living in 1999, kiddies.

it sucks that you consider dj'ing you job.  most people i talk to consider 
it an "art", like painting or writing.  they may not get paid for it, but 
they sure enjoy it, and they enjoy sharing it with other people.  no one is 
asking you to dj, buy records each week, and drive to the party without 
establishing that its cool to play for free first.  if its not cool, say no. 
  sit at home.  enjoy the "nite off" from your "work".

<3,
kali

Subject: RE: [sfraves] (Review) Furious

I just think there's too much emphasis on the dj getting paid some 
ridiculous ammount of $$ for playing records. Look at how negatively the "DJ 
as rock star" phenomenon affected the scene a few years back. Granted - 
those are two different scales monetarily speaking. Most local dj's don't 
get paid 100's of dollars to spin for a couple hours. Still, it's relatively 
little effort and doesn't seem to warrant a ton of dough for what's 
involved.

Sorry I'm not that materially driven.

M-

>get over yourself.  dj's aren't that special.
>
>its all about supply and demand--  basically, there are more kids out there 
>that would like to dj than would like to get paid to dj.  what makes you 
>think you deserve cash, when promoters are bringing in just enough (even 
>with expensive ticket prices) to pay their top headliners, and then break 
>even on the partay?  if anyone things there are promoters out there making 
>"gobs of cash" on anything, than i hate to break it to you, but you are 
>living in 1999, kiddies.
>
>it sucks that you consider dj'ing you job.  most people i talk to consider 
>it an "art", like painting or writing.  they may not get paid for it, but 
>they sure enjoy it, and they enjoy sharing it with other people.  no one is 
>asking you to dj, buy records each week, and drive to the party without 
>establishing that its cool to play for free first.  if its not cool, say 
>no.  sit at home.  enjoy the "nite off" from your "work".

Subject: RE: [sfraves] (Review) Furious

I wasn't insinuating you were. I was just stating that I'm not. I mean, I 
guess it's nice when people pay you to spin. I know I have gotten paid some 
decent $$ a few times, but I don't ask for it - it's a personal choice. To 
me, it's exciting just to be able to spin in front of people, and get the 
opportunity to make them dance.

If a person is literally LIVING off of spinning, then I guess maybe it's a 
different ball-game. But most people do it as a hobby. I don't know a whole 
lot of folks who get paid regularly to indulge their hobbies (short of 
people who grown the ganja anyway, lol).

It just seems to me that the people who are really down for the whole 
"family" vibe tend to be less about getting paid then sharing something with 
the group. Just my own observation.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] (Review) Furious

In an ideal world, neither promoters nor DJs would have dollar signs for
eyes. :b I think the best parties have, as an enormous component, humility
-- the crew, the DJs are there because they love music and they love their
little Temporary Autonomous Zones and they want to create a beautiful,
amazing experience. They aren't there to make a buck.

However, if there's going to be money made -- I think the DJ should be
taking something home before the guy throwing the party. If this doesn't
make any sense to you, I give you the record companies vs the artists in
commercial music. Record company makes millions, artist makes chump
change. If art is going to be sold, the artist should be the one making
money. :)

S

---
Griffin
Department of Disinformation

http://www.DefSF.com - 97.4% techno

I mean... they be like hella fun 2 hang out w/ & stuff/.... & they spin like such an Eclectic mis of music like all in the same set... I Love it man!!!  Can't really remember what they were spinning last Thurs night when I got... I vagely remember some Electro Clash Male vocals that night from their set...

LoL.. Then she busted out w/ 80's music like all of a sudden.. OK.. I do remember she played Billie Jean by MJ & David Bowie.. brain fart on the song... but it was sooo damn fun!!  I was hangin' out w/ these people out side.. like 4 of them knew me from friendster 'cause we were all connected by like 1-3 pepole... funny... LoL!!!  It was fun man...   Vibe was totaly CooL & I was meeting some groovy people there that night...LoL

It was funny.. there was this other group of Groovers i waws hangin' out w/ & they were all like over 6'2 (guys & girls) & i felt like this mondo short 5'8 1/2 shortie.. Hello 2Day...

4 the rest of the time i was there.. it was just an 80's dance floor heaven.. Yum!

I mean... i couldn't really stay 2 long 'cause of the whole last bart, bus thing 2 get 2 Hercules.. but i really had sooooooo much fun!!!  It really fun dancing w/ Sarah Delush while she's spinning & I'm on the floor!!

Good Stuff =) I can't wait 2 hang out w/ every1 there again soon =)

Subject: [sfraves] Dj Wavelength's Turntables and the Dungeon, an apology.

Well everyone,
     It appears that I made an error in my post about turntables being held 
for ransom.  The other evening when I was discussing a number of issues with 
DJ Wavelength, I misunderstood the situation of his turntables remaining at 
the Dungeon, the Bush and Van Ness venue, after his party.  After further 
investigating of the situation, I am offering a formal apology to him, Jared 
(the proprietor), and each of you that was unintentionally misled.  It was 
not my intention to hurt or wrongfully accuse anyone of anything.  I was 
simply posting insight on what I thought was the truth.  Unfortunately, 
sometimes things are presented in a manner so that they are unclear and the 
mind has a clevor way of filling in the gaps on its own.  In anycase, my 
current understanding of the situation is that the table were not in fact 
held for ransom and it was business deal that ended somewhat beneficiently 
for both parties.  Lo siento~~

-Joey Frisco

In-Reply-To: <BAY10-F59A6EMRPj0r200022f5f@hotmail.com>

MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] (Review) Furious

You seem very... avid.

My point here is not to point out the unique specialness of DJs. It's that
if the guy putting the records down and rocking the crowd isn't that
special...

Neither is the promoter. Neither are the organizers. They're diverse
elements that come together to help make a rave. If anything, respect
should be going out to the kids that show up and hug their
friends/complete strangers, dance their asses off, have crazy
conversations about space/time in the corner, smoke cigarettes, share some
chems, whatever. Because /at the heart of the party/ is the participants.

A rave is not a rock event. Throwing raves that don't show a profit, and
in fact barely pull even, is a labor of love - not just on the part of the
DJs or the promoters, but of /every human being/ that shows up. Everyone
who's come out to support their own little society with its own rules and
social codes and beliefs.

But. The fact is? Raves have changed.

Now it's hard to bring yourself to even use the word 'rave'. They're
'parties'. Or, if you listen very carefully before and after the music
starts bumping, when the big shots talk shit and shop, you'll hear the
word 'show', like it's a  fucking AC/DC concert.

Promoters want to make money. There isn't as much money to be made now as
their was 5 years ago, or even 3. But where there's a nickel to be made,
people will scrap and scrape and scratch for whatever they can pinch. You
hear all the time 'I don't make any money' -- the truth is, they just
don't make /enough/ money to satiate themselves. And they never will.
That's how greed works -- it's /never enough/.

but. Back to my point: if money is going to be made, that money should be
going to the artists. Not the junior businessmen.

S
---
Griffin
Department of Disinformation

http://www.DefSF.com - 97.4% techno

To: Van Mundegaarde <electrofunk138@hotmail.com>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] (Review) Furious


On Tue, 30 Mar 2004, Van Mundegaarde wrote:
-&e->I dunno - I spin, and I tend to think that dj's shouldn't get paid in
-&e->much more than gas money or free cocktails. But then again, I play
-&e->because I love it, not cuz I think I'm a rock star.

So the promoter pockets your humility?

Stupid.

I've been doing this for a long time, and I think there is a substantial
difference between a Ben Long or DJ Assault (seasoned veterans with
massive tecnical ability, a unique style, draw and records out) and a
newbie just starting to go beyond the bedroom crapping their shorts on 32
count smoothmixes at obvious "mix here" points.  Draw, experience, costs
incurred, technical ability, demand... no reason why you can't charge more
for a better / more developed / proven product.

If the party is for profit, charge for your services.  If its a free
party, or you're helping throw it within a collective, or it's a benefit
go ahead and play for free.  You pay real money for your records, you paid
real money for decks, needles, mixer, etc.  Your name appears on
promotional materials (marketing and cobranding), the promoter banks on
your draw (customer aquisition) and ability to move a crowd and make them
want to come back again (customer retention)... when you play for free you
undercut people asking a small reasonable fee that might not have the
excess cash on hand to support their DJing without compensation.

andyw

>You seem very... avid.
>
>My point here is not to point out the unique specialness of DJs. It's that
>if the guy putting the records down and rocking the crowd isn't that
>special...
>
>Neither is the promoter. Neither are the organizers. They're diverse
>elements that come together to help make a rave. If anything, respect
>should be going out to the kids that show up and hug their
>friends/complete strangers, dance their asses off, have crazy
>conversations about space/time in the corner, smoke cigarettes, share some
>chems, whatever. Because /at the heart of the party/ is the participants.
>
>A rave is not a rock event. Throwing raves that don't show a profit, and
>in fact barely pull even, is a labor of love - not just on the part of the
>DJs or the promoters, but of /every human being/ that shows up. Everyone
>who's come out to support their own little society with its own rules and
>social codes and beliefs.
>
>But. The fact is? Raves have changed.
>
>Now it's hard to bring yourself to even use the word 'rave'. They're
>'parties'. Or, if you listen very carefully before and after the music
>starts bumping, when the big shots talk shit and shop, you'll hear the
>word 'show', like it's a  fucking AC/DC concert.
>
>Promoters want to make money. There isn't as much money to be made now as
>their was 5 years ago, or even 3. But where there's a nickel to be made,
>people will scrap and scrape and scratch for whatever they can pinch. You
>hear all the time 'I don't make any money' -- the truth is, they just
>don't make /enough/ money to satiate themselves. And they never will.
>That's how greed works -- it's /never enough/.
>
>but. Back to my point: if money is going to be made, that money should be
>going to the artists. Not the junior businessmen.
>

>On Tue, 30 Mar 2004, Van Mundegaarde wrote:
>-&e->I dunno - I spin, and I tend to think that dj's shouldn't get paid in
>-&e->much more than gas money or free cocktails. But then again, I play
>-&e->because I love it, not cuz I think I'm a rock star.
>
>So the promoter pockets your humility?
>
>Stupid.
>
>I've been doing this for a long time, and I think there is a substantial
>difference between a Ben Long or DJ Assault (seasoned veterans with
>massive tecnical ability, a unique style, draw and records out) and a
>newbie just starting to go beyond the bedroom crapping their shorts on 32
>count smoothmixes at obvious "mix here" points.  Draw, experience, costs
>incurred, technical ability, demand... no reason why you can't charge more
>for a better / more developed / proven product.
>
>If the party is for profit, charge for your services.  If its a free
>party, or you're helping throw it within a collective, or it's a benefit
>go ahead and play for free.  You pay real money for your records, you paid
>real money for decks, needles, mixer, etc.  Your name appears on
>promotional materials (marketing and cobranding), the promoter banks on
>your draw (customer aquisition) and ability to move a crowd and make them
>want to come back again (customer retention)... when you play for free you
>undercut people asking a small reasonable fee that might not have the
>excess cash on hand to support their DJing without compensation.
>
>andyw

a resident and taxpayer DEMAND more accommodation for dance,=20
alternative, and after-hours culture and will NOT support additional=20
funding for government agencies that pass unnecessary prohibitions on=20
the free expression of this culture at places like Ocean Beach.

    From the GGNRA regulations for Ocean Beach:

=E2=80=A2 In respect of other park visitors, amplified music is prohibited.=20
Acoustic music will be considered. Exceptions can be made for portable=20
tape decks or CD players if discussed in advance with the Office of=20
Special Park Uses. Standing speakers, disk jockeys, public address=20
systems or any other type of amplified device are prohibited.

=E2=80=A2 Fires, candles, tiki torches and all other forms of open flame are=
=20
prohibited.

    There is also an oblique reference to how well they are spending our=20
money now:

=E2=80=A2 All trash associated with your private event must be bagged and=20
removed from the Park. Please make certain that someone in your group=20
is assigned to remove trash and decorations after your event or you=20
will be billed for staff overtime at $65.00 per hour.

    Who else but the government would spend $65 an hour to have trash=20
picked up on the beach? Are you being "served?" I hope everyone=20
remembers this the next time they see a bond measure on their ballot=20
asking for more money for parks.

Peace, love & liberty,
                        <<< Starchild >>>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] (Review) Furious

andyw, we seem to agree.  but many people would argue with your "no reason 
to charge more for the extra skills" idea.  many people come out to see 
their friends, their peers, evolve as dj's;  they don't believe its about 
the "mad skills".  they believe its more about watching a dream come into a 
reality.  does that make sense?

and yes, when dj's play for free they are undercutting the dj who might not 
be able to make it without compensation.  its a tough world out there, and 
if you can't afford records, or aren't willing to start out at the bottom of 
the totem pole, don't you think its fair to say you just might not make it?  
the rich will undermine the poor unless their exceptionally talented in ANY 
situation, how would this one be any different?

and its great that you've been doing this for a while now...  you wouldn't 
say that your views, were, oh, slightly jaded or rather firm and unopen to 
other arguments, would you?

<3,
kali

Subject: Re: [sfraves] (Review) Furious

(in reference to the idea that a dj who plays for free is undercutting a
struggling dj)

I play for free most of the time. I did when I lived in DC and was playing a
few times a week, and I do out here as well (probably moreso because no-one
knows who the hell I am, lol).

But, I am in no way, shape or form "rich". I don't play for free to undercut
anyone. I do it because as I stated earlier, I love to play, and the
opporunity to do it is like gold to me. I hardly think I'm taking away
chances from any struggling dj's though. If I am - maybe they need to
practice more ;)

M-

Hey folks,

There is a certain project that I am involved with, that some of you may or
may not be aware of. Regardless, we are on the lookout to begin recruiting
people with a minimum of 3 years sales experience. You will be on the ground
floor of a new company, selling something that has no competition.
Experience in the retail market is a huge plus. I cannot go into full detail
here, but, hit me back off forum to get more detail. This is definitely a
great opportunity if you are in sales and looking for something refreshing
and new.

Anyway, just wanted to extend the opportunity to my SFR family. If you are
into this, or know of someone who is, please feel free to forward this onto
appropriate parties. Also, you can send your resume to me and I will make
sure it finds its way to the right person.

PS - no this isn't a pyramid scam, we have physical product ready to go.
Huge commission opportunities.

Triumph out.

Subject: [sfraves] Re: Pay for DJs (was: Furious review)

	Hmm... I like what Andy W said (play for pay at for-profit =
parties, =20
for free at free parties), but I wouldn't go so far as to say a DJ =20
should always make money before a promoter. Organizing a good rave is =20=

in many ways an artistic endeavor. Think of all the creative things =20
that a promoter does or has a hand in making decisions about:  flier =20
design, lighting, decoration, etc. There is also the fact that DJs =20
generally enjoy spinning more than promoters enjoy many aspects of =20
promotion such as negotiating with space owners, stressing about =20
preparations, dealing with fights, busts, and medical emergencies, and =20=

the other million things that can come up. Isn't the person who has to =20=

deal with unpleasant responsibilities more deserving of compensation =20
than the artist doing what he or she loves?

	Of course this is all just my two cents on how things would =
ideally =20
happen. In the real world, each action and decision of a participant =20
who exchanges money or services in our scene (promoters, DJs, ravers, =20=

etc.) combine to represent the collective input of the whole community =20=

better than any one individual or group possibly could, and this =20
determines how much compensation is generally available for different =20=

work. This is what Adam Smith (the "father of capitalism") meant by the =20=

"invisible hand" of the free market.

Groove on,
					<<< Starchild >>>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] (Review) Furious

I'd agree - wanking an EQ around and beatmatching is not an art.

Mixing, however, is creating a piece of composite art from a collection of
other people's art. Just because it isn't production (and, believe me,
a -lot- of analog artists -- you know, the ones who use instruments --
really don't think using synths and software counts as making music, or
any kind of real art) doesn't mean there isn't art to it. I would say the
difference between a good DJ and a bad one is someone who wanks the EQ
and beatmatches, and someone who -is- an artist. ;)

And I don't DJ. Nor have I ever made a single dollar off of any DJ's work.
;)

---
Griffin
Department of Disinformation

http://www.DefSF.com - 97.4% techno

At 04:41 PM 3/30/2004, Nathan Seven wrote:
>--- Sean G <srg@pdx.edu> wrote:
> >
> > If art is going to be sold, the artist
> > should be the one making
> > money. :)
>
>Hmmm- that's interestingly poetic, since most DJs play
>other people's music...

Hmmm....do other DJs out there get their vinyl for free?:)  If it were not 
for us playing other people's music I would think the producers of those 
works would be on the streets selling apples.


>Scratching and "turntablism" is an art, wanking an EQ
>around and beatmatching is not.
>What say you put your money where your mouth is and
>send all of your DJ earnings to all of the producers
>of the tracks you just got paid for playing?

DJs support the music producers, and I assume the producers create records 
to sell them to DJs.  My monthly vinyl bill is amazing at times even to me, 
and I've come to see it as some sort of addiction.  But it is a passion and 
I assume spinning is for others, whether they do it at home or for the 
public.  Creation of an interesting, engaging and danceable track list 
requires much outlay for records and other equipment.  Most of us are 
motivated, I think, by a desire to share the music we love with 
others.  Not financial return.

I know very few people in the mix who actually make a living at it.  I've 
never made pocket change, and that really has been a decision on my part.

As for producing underground parties,  I wouldn't undertake that very hard 
work and great risk for any money.  If I, and the unselfish people I work 
with, were not motivated by non-monetary values we simply wouldn't throw 
'em.  Same can be said for many other collectives in our community.

Much love,

Apollo



Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

the children of humans as a whole experience it.  Avoiding danger is no 
safer in the long run than outright exposure.  Life is either a daring 
adventure or nothing."
-Helen Keller

The dangerous patriot: "The one who drifts into chauvinism and exhibits 
blind enthusiasm for military actions. He is a defender of militarism and 
its ideals of war and glory. Chauvinism is a proud and bellicose form of 
patriotism . . . which identifies numerous enemies who can only be dealt 
with through military power and which equates the national honor with 
military victory..."
-Marine Corps, Colonel James A. Donovan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

>
>Scratching and "turntablism" is an art, wanking an EQ
>around and beatmatching is not.

This is a pretty popular though these days and it's sad.

Not sad because people think that, they have a reason to. It's that reason 
that makes it sad. A real QUALITY deejay does soooo much more than just 
that. Unfortunaltely, 99% of deejays are not in that catagory. So most 
people thinks that's all a real deejay does.

beatmatch".

>What say you put your money where your mouth is and
>send all of your DJ earnings to all of the producers
>of the tracks you just got paid for playing?

A 12" import vinyl release costs around $12 these days. It's not our fault 
that the artist will only see about $1 of that. Besides, any good producer's 
deejay booking fee goes up 3-10 fold once they start releasing quality 
music. They ARE getting paid because other people are playing thier music in 
a round-about way. Most tracks sold these days take 5-20 hours to produce as 
well. Not too much work. It's not all THAT much more important than who's 
playing them. If at all.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-Deejay Gavin Varitech
(916) 733-1615 - Bookings/info
(916) 412-3313 - Contact
www.techwesttribe.com

Subject: RE: [sfraves] (Review) Furious

I do get paid actually. Thats why you dont see my name that much on rave 
flyers. Trust me, I get asked to play by new-jack promoters all the time but 
unfortunately have to refuse many of the bookings. And also trust that I'm 
willing to play for what would be considered a very light fee compared to 
what people (including me) was making just a few years back. SO it's not 
that I'm asking for too much. Unless too much is asking for anything.

It's really sad to me that people get mad when someone feel's that they are 
worth something as a deejay. Not only that, my time is worth a lot (TO ME) 
and playing at a shitty party for a few dollars is not worth all the hastle 
it involves anymore.

If I'm confident the party is going to be truly dope, most good deejays are 
more than willing to play for way less than they are used to. If I'm that 
confident, I'll play for next to nothing too.

Starchild <sfdreamer@earthlink.net> wrote:
Good call, Daddy! Are those who agree that there should be more of 
this kind of thing (a proposition with which I heartily agree) are 
willing to lift a finger to help make it so?

If you are, please call the Golden Gate National Recreation Area 
Office of Special Park Uses at (415) 561-4300 and tell them that you as 
a resident and taxpayer DEMAND more accommodation for dance, 
alternative, and after-hours culture and will NOT support additional 
funding for government agencies that pass unnecessary prohibitions on 
the free expression of this culture at places like Ocean Beach.

>From the GGNRA regulations for Ocean Beach:

 In respect of other park visitors, amplified music is prohibited. 
Acoustic music will be considered. Exceptions can be made for portable 
tape decks or CD players if discussed in advance with the Office of 
Special Park Uses. Standing speakers, disk jockeys, public address 
systems or any other type of amplified device are prohibited.

 Fires, candles, tiki torches and all other forms of open flame are 
prohibited.

There is also an oblique reference to how well they are spending our 
money now:

 All trash associated with your private event must be bagged and 
removed from the Park. Please make certain that someone in your group 
is assigned to remove trash and decorations after your event or you 
will be billed for staff overtime at $65.00 per hour.

Who else but the government would spend $65 an hour to have trash 
picked up on the beach? Are you being "served?" I hope everyone 
remembers this the next time they see a bond measure on their ballot 
asking for more money for parks.

Peace, love & liberty,
<<< Starchild >>>

Subject: [sfraves] Who Remeber's the Russian Loft Venue?

OK.. so like that was 1 of my favorite spots ever in SF 'cause well... parties were were like always good vibe, Groovy Energy, & oh my goodness man.. I'd always meet people from around the country @ a party there... incidently... i took my 1st pill there like ummmmm.. how many years ago... Hello 2day.. la la la...

But the thing about the Raves there was that well... they were always over crowded, over capacity, but still fun as fuckin' hell!  There was only 1 dance floor on the top of the stairway & like this huuuuuge upstairs room that was always hot when hell filled up w/ people... It's like the dungeon venue in some ways in that aspect, ya know... but back in the day though... it wasn't really ummm.. a threat 2 police I guess 'cause well ok yeah.. they did catch on finally after a while... but b4 then, people were allowed 2 go in & out, there was a chill room like on the side of the stair way in the building.. it was Dope!  This was like totally back in the day well... thinkin' about it... there wasn't hardcore 1015 wannabe security people workin' the door, ok, drugs were done like lilesurely & openly @ this spot, there weren't like 2 many Candy Kids hangin out but alot... i do have like Bad Ass Memories of raves there!

I dunno... i was just like recollecting on old school venues when that thread was goin' on & all those complaints & shit, but ya know... I realize that's how like the Dopest Memories are made @ venues like those...

OK.. so like my 2 cents anyway... but man... I"m all getting fuckin' nostalgic now... LoL... damn... I remember this 1 party @ the Russian Loft when i had my 1st ever like Raver Family... it was so Dope!

I think i kinda lost my train of thought on what my point was, but like people hate venues that other people Love going 2 simply 4 the fact that they wouldn't know any better... furious made it like the 4th time i been there i think & I jus well... yeah.. it does get hot as hell, but they did open up another like airy room where people can cool out... & there was like vented areas & fans in ever room that u could stand by...

BUt yeah.. that furious thread just remeinded me of the Russian loft & I wonder if anyone else partied there 2? =)

Good Times!

"Peter Jennings Reporting: Ecstasy Rising"
Airs Thursday, April 1st, on ABC at 10PM EST

ABC NEWS TO AIR ONE-HOUR SPECIAL REPORT ON
TODAY'S DRUG OF CHOICE -- ECSTASY


The rise of Ecstasy is a major event in drug history. If current trends
continue, 1.8 million Americans will try Ecstasy for the first time in
2004; only marijuana will attract more new users. Overwhelming, positive
word of mouth has made Ecstasy a nightmare for drug controllers. On a
special edition of "Primetime Thursday," Peter Jennings tells the epic
story of Ecstasy that has never been heard. "Peter Jennings Reporting:
Ecstasy Rising" airs THURSDAY, APRIL 1st at 10pm EST on the ABC
Television Network.

In the 1990s, Ecstasy seemed to come out of nowhere to join marijuana,
cocaine and heroin as one of the four most widely used illegal drugs in
the country. No other drug has ever spread so fast.

To halt its spread, the U.S. Government has spent millions of dollars
making a dramatic case against Ecstasy as a dangerous drug. The headline
of this campaign has been that Ecstasy causes massive brain damage. But
this is a claim based on flawed science, and many Ecstasy users now feel
their government has no credibility.

What do we know about the real risks of Ecstasy? Has the government been
its own worst enemy in the fight to stop the drug's use?

"Peter Jennings Reporting: Ecstasy Rising" takes viewers through the
seminal events in this story and introduces all the major players --
from Alexander Shulgin, the famous chemist who was the first person to
report the effects of Ecstasy, to Michael Clegg, the Dallas businessman
who gave Ecstasy its name and turned it into a recreational drug, to the
drug enforcement officer who led the fight to make Ecstasy illegal, to
the DJ who brought Rave to America. This special tells the definitive
story of how an obscure compound, discovered in 1912 and all but
forgotten for over 60 years, became the drug of choice for a generation.


Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.net

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm




"A human being is part of a whole, called by us the 'Universe,' a part 
limited in time and space. He experiences himself, his thoughts and 
feelings, as something separated from the rest--a kind of optical delusion 
of his consciousness. This delusion is a kind of prison for us, restricting 
us to our personal desires and to affection for a few persons nearest us. 
Our task must be to free ourselves from this prison by widening our circles 
of compassion to embrace all living creatures and the whole of nature in 
its beauty."
-Albert Einstein

OK.. so like that was 1 of my favorite spots ever in SF 'cause well... parties were were like always good vibe, Groovy Energy, & oh my goodness man.. I'd always meet people from around the country @ a party there... incidently... i took my 1st pill there like ummmmm.. how many years ago... Hello 2day.. la la la...

But the thing about the Raves there was that well... they were always over crowded, over capacity, but still fun as fuckin' hell! There was only 1 dance floor on the top of the stairway & like this huuuuuge upstairs room that was always hot when hell filled up w/ people... It's like the dungeon venue in some ways in that aspect, ya know... but back in the day though... it wasn't really ummm.. a threat 2 police I guess 'cause well ok yeah.. they did catch on finally after a while... but b4 then, people were allowed 2 go in & out, there was a chill room like on the side of the stair way in the building.. it was Dope! This was like totally back in the day well... thinkin' about it... there wasn't hardcore 1015 wannabe security people workin' the door, ok, drugs were done like lilesurely & openly @ this spot, there weren't like 2 many Candy Kids hangin out but alot... i do have like Bad Ass Memories of raves there!

I dunno... i was just like recollecting on old school venues when that thread was goin' on & all those complaints & shit, but ya know... I realize that's how like the Dopest Memories are made @ venues like those...

OK.. so like my 2 cents anyway... but man... I"m all getting fuckin' nostalgic now... LoL... damn... I remember this 1 party @ the Russian Loft when i had my 1st ever like Raver Family... it was so Dope!

I think i kinda lost my train of thought on what my point was, but like people hate venues that other people Love going 2 simply 4 the fact that they wouldn't know any better... furious made it like the 4th time i been there i think & I jus well... yeah.. it does get hot as hell, but they did open up another like airy room where people can cool out... & there was like vented areas & fans in ever room that u could stand by...

BUt yeah.. that furious thread just remeinded me of the Russian loft & I wonder if anyone else partied there 2? =)

Good Times!

Van Mundegaarde <electrofunk138@hotmail.com> said...
> That's the way it goes down in DC. If a venue ownder dicks people, people 
> tend to boycott them. The sad truth is however, that they'll just get some 
> other crowd to fuck over....
> 
> M-

If it's a habitual problem at that space, and it's at the
level where people's safety is becoming a real issue:

Write the spaceowner a letter (snail mail) with your concerns.
You're really concerned about someone becoming dehydrated
or about egress issues in case of an emergency from severe
overcrowding. You don't want to cause official intervention, but
would appreciate it if they would work with future partythrowers
to address these issues.

Then the next time it happens, get them busted. Parties aren't
worth anyone getting injured or dying.

Sean

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Who Remeber's the Russian Loft Venue?

That's the Zanes' place. Dancehauz, aka *gingerbread warehouse*, aka Army
and Conneticut. It's still around here and there, but mostly for some 21+
type events. I remember that place before it was remodeled and that upstairs
floor looked like it was going to collapse. I had a gf break her ankle on
the stairs prior to the rails being installed. Fast forward to today and the
place is completely remodeled and gorgeous. It's a dance studio and fully
licensed as such. Took about 4 years for all of that to occur, but now it's
nice. Almost too nice to throw a party in these days...

:: r ::

FYI:

information regarding the production of this special report.

From: Susan C. Schaefer
Date: Wed, 31 Mar 2004 10:08:56 -0500
Subject: documentary

Hey all -

A while back I was in touch with you and others at hyperreal about
trying to get interview candidates for a Peter Jennings Documentary on
Ecstasy (and some of you actually helped put me in touch with some great
people). I wanted to contact you as the documentary is finally airing
this Thursday, April 1st at 10PM EST ( I think 9PM PT?) on ABC (channel
7). It's entitled "Peter Jennings Reporting: Ecstasy Rising" and I think
you'll find that what we report about Ecstasy is unprecedented for a
major news network. I am attaching some information about the program
below. I encourage you to pass the information along to anyone you think
might be interested in watching (especially the hyperreal community). I
think you will enjoy the show and would love to know what you think of
it. The network was actually quite hesitant to air this show because
they thought it was too controversial. So we'd love your support to show
them that they have done the right thing.

All the best,

Susan

Susan C. Schaefer

PJ Productions


 "Peter Jennings Reporting: Ecstasy Rising"

Airs Thursday, April 1st, on ABC at 10PM EST


ABC NEWS TO AIR ONE-HOUR SPECIAL REPORT ON

TODAY'S DRUG OF CHOICE -- ECSTASY


The rise of Ecstasy is a major event in drug history. If current trends
continue, 1.8 million Americans will try Ecstasy for the first time in
2004; only marijuana will attract more new users. Overwhelming, positive
word of mouth has made Ecstasy a nightmare for drug controllers. On a
special edition of "Primetime Thursday," Peter Jennings tells the epic
story of Ecstasy that has never been heard. "Peter Jennings Reporting:
Ecstasy Rising" airs THURSDAY, APRIL 1st at 10pm EST on the ABC
Television Network.


In the 1990s, Ecstasy seemed to come out of nowhere to join marijuana,
cocaine and heroin as one of the four most widely used illegal drugs in
the country. No other drug has ever spread so fast.


To halt its spread, the U.S. Government has spent millions of dollars
making a dramatic case against Ecstasy as a dangerous drug. The headline
of this campaign has been that Ecstasy causes massive brain damage. But
this is a claim based on flawed science, and many Ecstasy users now feel
their government has no credibility.


What do we know about the real risks of Ecstasy? Has the government been
its own worst enemy in the fight to stop the drug's use?


"Peter Jennings Reporting: Ecstasy Rising" takes viewers through the
seminal events in this story and introduces all the major players --
from Alexander Shulgin, the famous chemist who was the first person to
report the effects of Ecstasy, to Michael Clegg, the Dallas businessman
who gave Ecstasy its name and turned it into a recreational drug, to the
drug enforcement officer who led the fight to make Ecstasy illegal, to
the DJ who brought Rave to America. This special tells the definitive
story of how an obscure compound, discovered in 1912 and all but
forgotten for over 60 years, became the drug of choice for a generation.

I don't know if any of you know Eugene Gorenman [was a major force in =
the GarageSF crew, a local Russian dance/party collective], but I have =
some bad news. It appears that last Sunday my good friend was mugged and =
gunned down in a SF park at night. He is dead.=20

If you did know him, I am sure this will come as a shock. I found out =
myself today at Lunch. Eugene was one of the most intelligent, caring =
and funny men I have ever had the pleasure of calling my good friend. =
There is nothing he wouldn't do for his friends and the love and =
personal qualities he had for people is something I still try and mimic =
to this day. He was responsible for my very first SF club booking a few =
years back and helped me get my foot in the door at other venues. I will =
miss him very dearly as I am sure you will. Rather than sending flowers, =
should it empower you, I would ask that you make a donation to a =
worthwhile charity in his name instead. That is the type of person =
Eugene was and I am sure he would want the same.=20

So by the powers vested in me as an under-paid, over-taxed Californian, =
I hereby declare March 31st "Eugene Gorenman Day". I am sure Cesar =
Chavez wouldn't object. And tonight in honor of my good Russian friend, =
drink some vodka, and raise a toast towards the heaven's.

Hello 2Day... Gosh man.. so good 2 C him again after so Long...

Kicked it w/ The Doc while he was there... I swear man.. he's so fun 2 hang out w/ always got asmile on his face & lol.. i always think back on when I wqas sooo scared of him...

Then Sharp went on & like it was Cool... Oh My gosh man.. see... I can't describe how the sets were other then they were all fuckin' what i needed man... Sharp brought it up another notch on the hard ass Jungle scale, LoL, & played some wicked shit... Gosh man... I'm such a newbie Junglist after all these years... grrrr.... but it was just good though man... I Loved his set!!!  Oh shit man... he also has this Bad Ass CD that he gave me a while back that i listen 2 alot!

OK... I know 4 a fact that 4 Real spun this Awesome fucin' set 'cause he spun a strictly 96-97 Jungle set & I swear man... oooooh man... I Loe those Old Tracks...I fuckin' Creamed when i heard all the DNB yumminess pouring outta the speakers!!!

OK... I told him I was gonna lie about hearing the tag set, but I know that DJ M & Sopund boy did a fuck bang up job as i know both their styles of spinning & track selection, but like I know DJ M will through in surprises along the way & you're like WTF... but I know they did a Did a Groovy job 'cause we left during 4 Real's set!!

Ok... the Vibe was on when we were there!!  LoL... Me, Mariposa, & Audio Angel fuckin' dominated the dancefloor!!  Good Shit... it was this energy that the 3 of were sharing 2gether & we danced like wild fuckin' people.. oh gosh man... gasp

I mean... ofcourse it was Groovy seein' all the poeple i saw there 'cauise yeah... JuJu, Mal aka Jamalcom, Ivory, Ian, Raze, oh gosh man... Loved it!!!

I reeeeeeeeeeeeally wanna make it next week 4 the 6 year anniversay man... I could only imagine who's gonna show up there... good shit man... I'll even bart it & crash @ aome1's pad if I have 2!!!

Wow.... =)

Take Care,
Peace-> ObY {8O)

Subject: [sfraves] Raving in the UK

--=====================_30959928==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed


Police used CS spray at rave

<mailto:richard.balls@archant.co.uk>RICHARD BALLS

March 31, 2004 07:19 Norfolk

Norfolk police last night admitted using CS gas to disperse revellers 
during the break-up of an illegal rave at a disused warehouse near Norwich 
airport.

Chief Insp Nick Dean, the officer in charge of the operation, said CS gas 
was deployed after around 100 youths had hurled bottles and displayed 
"severe aggression" towards officers, who had descended on the vacant 
premises off Hurricane Way on the Airport Industrial Estate early on Sunday.

The only person taken to hospital during the 12-hour operation was a police 
officer, who suffered a broken hand, although other officers were 
"physically attacked" during scuffles with a hardcore group who barricaded 
themselves in, he said.

But ravers accused officers of using excessive force and said CS gas had 
been sprayed into the building from the outset, affecting many of those who 
had been dancing to the music inside.

Police had also beaten people with batons, leaving many with bruises to 
their arms and legs and one girl with a broken arm. One eye-witness said he 
had seen officers smashing the windows of a vehicle at the premises and 
using batons on the occupants.

Darren Keaton, 20, from Norwich, said: "I was right at the back of the room 
and I could feel the fumes burning in the back of my mouth. There were 
about eight officers in a row who were using the spray.

"A 16-year-old girl was smashed in the face and her whole top was covered 
in blood. Some officers saw her being carried out past them and moved to 
one side to let the other ravers come in, I think because they realised 
they had done wrong. And all this was at the beginning."

Harry Samkin, 18, said he had also witnessed the use of CS spray.

"I was right at the other end, so it must have been sprayed throughout the 
whole place. I could feel it in my throat."

Chief Insp Dean, of Norwich police, confirmed that CS gas had been 
dispersed at the very earliest stages of the operation, but he could not 
say whether it had been used in the warehouse.

The decision had been taken in the face of bottles being thrown at officers 
and "severe aggression" from 100 or so revellers, and because it was 
considered one of the only options available to officers to ensure their 
safety.

"The initial assessment made, having been faced with such aggression, was 
that we would try to communicate with the people inside the building and 
move them, warning that they were committing an offence and we were going 
to require them to leave," he said.

"In fairness, a number of people did leave the premises with no problems 
whatsoever. However, things escalated when the occupants came out and tried 
to move various vehicles from around the premises which we had a legal 
right to seize.

http://www.edp24.co.uk/content/News/story.asp?datetime=31+Mar+2004+07%3A19&tbrand=EDPOnline&tCategory=NEWS&category=News&brand=EDPOnline&itemid=NOED30+Mar+2004+20%3A20%3A36%3A200
